<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>The main issue before the trial judge in this case was whether when Mr. Wright transferred his 1/3 interest in the royalty (the &ldquo;Royalty Interest&rdquo;) from Crew Capital Corporation to the plaintiff in 1999, he intended to gift 50% of the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff or whether he transferred the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff with the sole intention that the plaintiff act as a nominee for him.</P>
<P>The trial judge committed palpable and overriding error by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence that went to the core of the case by, most notably:
<P1>i. Ignoring the entire evidence of Paul Royce, a neutral witness who was Mr. Wright and Crew Capital Corporation's accountant at all relevant times and therefore familiar with the royalty. Mr. Royce testified that Mr. Wright told him that David Long held the royalty as a nominee. Mr. Royce was an important witness for the defence, but his evidence is not even referred to in the trial judge's decision.</P1>
<P1>ii. Ignoring the entire evidence of Gail Wright, Mr. Wright's wife. The trial judge found that a 50% interest in the royalty was gifted to the plaintiff in 1999 by Mr. Wright, in part because Mr. Wright wanted to shelter the royalty from his wife. However, Ms. Wright testified that she was always familiar with the existence of the royalty and knew from the beginning that the respondent held the royalty solely as a nominee. Ms. Wright was an important witness for the defence, yet her evidence was not addressed in the trial judge's reasons. Ms. Wright's testimony was corroborated by contemporaneous documents that proved that she was aware of the Royalty Interest at the time of the transfer to the plaintiff, also not addressed by the trial judge.</P1></P>
<P>The trial judge also committed palpable and overriding error by failing to properly assess the credibility of the plaintiff and defendants.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1 STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. This case concerns whether Mr. Wright intended to gift the plaintiff 50% of the Royalty Interest when it was transferred to the plaintiff from Crew Capital Corporation in 1999, or whether Mr. Wright caused the Royalty Interest to be transferred to the plaintiff to hold solely as his nominee.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background</TI>
<P>2. The plaintiff, David Long, and the defendant, Gerald Wright, were long-time friends until there was a breakdown in their relationship in late June, 2011.
<P1>Appeal Record (&ldquo;AR&rdquo;), Reasons, paras. 1 and 38</P1></P>
<P>3. In June 1992, Crew Capital Corporation acquired a royalty in a prospective potash mine in Thailand being developed by Asia Pacific Resources (APR), through the efforts of its three shareholders: Gerald Wright, John Darch, and Bob Anderson.
<P1>AR, Reasons, para. 9</P1></P>
<P>4. APR was a public company listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange, and its primary business was the development of the Udon Thani pot ash project. Gerald Wright served as its President and CEO from 1992 to 2001.</P>
<P>5. In November 1997, the three shareholders of Crew Capital Corporation and Paul Royce, the company's chartered accountant, had a meeting to discuss the future of the company. It was agreed that the royalty would be sold to the three shareholders of the company, and that they would allow Crew Capital Corporation to be struck from the registry.
<P1>Appeal Book (&ldquo;AB&rdquo;), Vol. 1, p. 24</P1></P>
<P>6. On or about February 1999, Crew Capital Corporation entered into an agreement transferring the royalty in equal parts to Alice Anderson (Bob Anderson's wife), 540438 B.C. Ltd. (John Darch's company), and the plaintiff. The agreement is dated for reference November 28, 1997.
<P1>AB, Vo1. p. 72</P1></P>
<P>7. Each of the recipients of the 1/3<SUP>rd</SUP> interest in the royalty (the &ldquo;Royalty Interest&rdquo;) agreed to pay $13,333 by way of a promissory note made in favour of Crew Capital Corporation.</P>
<P>8. On February 19, 1999, Mr. Wright caused a company controlled by him, Cypress Consulting Services Inc., to transfer the funds necessary for the plaintiff to pay out the amount of the promissory note on February 26, 1999 (shortly before it was due).
<P1>AB, Vo. 1, pp. 100&ndash;103</P1></P>
<P>9. Around March 11, 1999, George Brazier, the corporate solicitor for Crew Capital Corporation, sent Mr. Wright a draft agreement transferring the Royalty Interest from the plaintiff to an entity to be filled in later by Mr. Wright on the agreement. The agreement was referred to as the &ldquo;Blank Agreement&rdquo; at the trial.
<P1>AB, Vol. 2, p. 705</P1></P>
<P>10. On May 4, 1999, Mr. Brazier made further changes to the Blank Agreement, and provided a copy of the Blank Agreement to Gail Wright under the cover of a note to her that states as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Gail, as requested, herewith corrected Agreement for David Long.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>AB, Vol. 1, p. 110</P1></P>
<P>11. Gail Wright provided the amended Blank Agreement received from Mr. Brazier to Mr. Wright, and Mr. Wright in turn he provided it to Mr. Long for execution. Mr. Long executed the Blank Agreement, according to Mr. Wright's evidence, sometime in the first week of July, 1999. Mr. Wright and Gail Wright's evidence is that the original Blank Agreement was then held in a safe in their home in West Vancouver.
<P1>AB, Vol. 1, p. 1</P1></P>
<P>12. The Blank Agreement transferred the entire Royalty Interest from David Long to an entity to be filled in by Mr. Wright, for &ldquo;$1.00 and other good and valuable consideration (the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged)&rdquo;. The Blank Agreement does not make any reference to David Long retaining any beneficial interest in the Royalty Interest.</P>
<P>13. On November 10, 2009, Red Branch Investments Limited was incorporated in Hong Kong. The shareholdings of the company are held by Mr. Wright (36.5%), Gail Wright (36.5%), and their three children (27%). The directors are Mr. Wright and Gail Wright.</P>
<P>14. The plaintiff executed an agreement dated for reference September 1, 2009, transferring the Royalty Interest to Red Branch Investments Limited for &ldquo;$1.00 and other good and valuable consideration (the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged)&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Red Branch Agreement&rdquo;). The Red Branch Agreement is almost identical to the Blank Agreement, and similarly does not make reference to David Long retaining any beneficial interest in the Royalty Interest.
<P1>AB, Vol. 2, pp. 448&ndash;450</P1></P>
<P>15. On July 7, 2010, Mr. Wright sent an email to Andrew Gabrielson, a solicitor at Fasken Martineau DuMoulin LLP, attaching a copy of the executed Red Branch Agreement, with the plaintiff copied. In the body of the email, Mr. Wright states that the royalty holder has changed by way of the Red Branch Agreement, and describes Red Branch as a &ldquo;Wright family company, based in Hong Kong, and I am a 36.5% shareholder&rdquo;. No reference is made in the email to the plaintiff having any beneficial interest in Red Branch.
<P1>AB, Vol. 2, pp. 482 - 483</P1></P>
<P>16. At least one year after the Red Branch Agreement is entered into, the plaintiff and Mr. Wright had a falling out and their friendship came to an end, related to their respective roles as directors of Amanta Resources, a mineral exploration company that was listed on the TSX Venture Exchange at the time.
<P1>AR, Reasons, para. 24</P1></P>
<P>17. On January 26, 2012, the plaintiff's asserts an interest in and makes a demand for the transfer of <TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC> of the Royalty Interest to him. Red Branch Investments Limited did not accede to the demand.
<P1>AB, Vol. 2, pp. 686 - 687</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Mr. Wright's explanation at trial for the 1999 transfer of the Royalty Interest to David Long</TI>
<P>18. Mr. Wright's evidence a trial was that he intended to hold the Royalty Interest overseas, and therefore asked the plaintiff to hold the Royalty Interest solely as his nominee until he was able to set up an overseas corporation in a tax efficient jurisdiction and transfer the Royalty Interest to it.</P>
<P>19. Mr. Wright also explained at trial that he asked Mr. Brazier to prepare the Blank Agreement, so that once he incorporated an overseas corporation he could use the Blank Agreement to transfer the royalty from the plaintiff.</P>
<P>20. The first draft of the Blank Agreement received from Mr. Brazier on March 11, 1999, contained the wrong address for the plaintiff, and because he was in Thailand he asked Mr. Brazier to correct the Blank Agreement and provide the corrected version to Gail Wright.</P>
<P>21. Mr. Wright further testified at trial that the executed Blank Agreement was kept in a safe at the family home in West Vancouver.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The plaintiff's explanation for the 1999 transfer of the Royalty Interest to him</TI>
<P>22. The plaintiff's evidence was that Mr. Wright gifted him 50% of the Royalty Interest in 1999 for the following reasons:
<P1>(a) They were life-long friends and business partners and Wright shared everything with him on a 50/50 basis;</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Wright was going to divorce his wife and did not want the Royalty Interest to become part of a divorce settlement with her; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Mr. Wright wanted to avoid having to pay any taxes in Canada that may be due if the royalty were to ever begin producing income.
<P2>Tr. Vol. 1, p. 185, ll. 1&ndash;47</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The trial judge's reasons</TI>
<P>23. The trial judge concluded that the 1999 transfer of the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff was &ldquo;an initial gift by Mr. Wright of 50% interest to the plaintiff&rdquo; and described the transfer as follows:
<QUOTE><P>(a) The plaintiff was to be the initial registered owner, until the royalty interest could be transferred ultimately to a yet to be determined overseas corporation and held in trust for the benefit of both the plaintiff and Mr. Wright on an equal beneficial ownership basis;</P>
<P>(b) <UNDER>The rationale behind this ploy was initially to shelter Mr. Wright's beneficial ownership from his wife in the event of a divorce</UNDER> and secondly to later park the ownership in an overseas holding corporation with a more favourable income taxation rate;</P>
<P>(c) After their falling-out, Mr. Wright reneged on his initial agreement with the plaintiff and Red Branch must now be construed as a trustee for the plaintiff's 50% interest in the royalty.
<P1>[Emphasis added]</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1>AR, Reasons, para. 6</P1></P>
<P>24. Therefore, the trial judge's finding that Mr. Wright transferred the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff in order to shelter it from Gail Wright, was an integral part of his decision.</P>
<P>25. In the &ldquo;Background&rdquo; section of his reasons, which forms the majority of the reasons, the trial judge essentially reviews, and appears to accept, the position and evidence called by the plaintiff at the trial. The trial judge does not in any meaningful way, consider the evidence of Mr. Wright, Paul Royce, or Gail Wright.</P>
<P>26. At paragraph 28 of his Reasons, the trial judge found that the plaintiff and Mr. Wright &ldquo;engaged in various business ventures in Ireland in the past&rdquo; and that the business relationships were arranged such that &ldquo;Mr. Wright funded them and Mr. Long operated them&rdquo;.</P>
<P>27. At trial, the plaintiff described two business ventures he had been involved in with Mr. Wright by 1999, Dublin Direct Limited and the Dublin Sports Caf&ea;. With respect to both businesses the plaintiff conceded that while the shareholdings of the companies were equally held by him and Mr. Wright, it was agreed that Mr. Wright's shareholder loans would be paid back first before any dividends were paid out the shareholders. The plaintiff agreed that he earned his shareholdings in the two companies by way of &ldquo;sweat equity&rdquo;.
<P1>Tr. Vol. 1, p. 156, ll. 7&ndash;38</P1>
<P1>Tr. Vol. 1, pp. 173 - 174</P1></P>
<P>28. There was no evidence at the trial of Mr. Wright ever having gifted the plaintiff any business interests, or of having granted the plaintiff an interest in any business that he was not involved in. The plaintiff earned his interest in the businesses that Mr. Wright invested in by way of &ldquo;sweat equity&rdquo;.</P>
<P>29. At paragraph 29 of his Reasons, the trial judge makes reference to litigation commenced in Ireland relating to the winding up of a business venture with the plaintiff. Mr. Wright funded the litigation, and shared the success of the litigation with the plaintiff 50/50.</P>
<P>30. As a result, the trial judge found that the gift of 50% of the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff, was &ldquo;entirely consistent with ventures that they had engaged in in the past&rdquo;.
<P1>AR, Reasons, para. 30</P1></P>
<P>31. The trial judge considered John Darch to be a neutral witness, having no bias in favour of either of the parties, and his evidence therefore was of particular importance to his findings. John Darch testified that Mr. Wright told him that he was appointing the plaintiff as his nominee for the royalty and that he intended to share the royalty with the plaintiff.
<P1>AR, Reasons, paras. 47&ndash;50</P1></P>
<P>32. The trial judge explained that he considered the plaintiff's version of events to be more probable, because:
<QUOTE><P>(1) The representation of a beneficial 50:50 share of the royalty is consistent with the past friendship and financial business relationship of the parties.</P>
<P>(2) Despite being warned by Mr. Darch about &ldquo;properly papering&rdquo;, the true nature of a shared 50:50 interest arrangement in the royalty transfer to Mr. Long, Mr. Wright chose not to leave a paper trail, ostensibly for personal domestic and taxation reasons. Mr. Darch in effect corroborated Mr. Long's assertion that Mr. Wright initially preferred a &ldquo;better a half than ultimately a quarter&rdquo; interest in the royalty.</P>
<P>(3) Although Mr. Wright is a sophisticated and experience businessman, he chose not to leave a traceable paper trail about the true nature of the transfer. He was concerned about potential tax consequences if the true nature of the transfer was papered. However, he could also have effected a private declaration of trust document himself and Mr. Long, known only between themselves.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>AR, Reasons, paras. 57</P1></P>
<P>33. The trial judge found that Mr. Wright decided to &ldquo;renege on their original agreement&rdquo; after the falling out between the parties.
<P1>AR, Reasons, para. 58</P1></P>
<P>34. As discussed in the argument below, the trial judge did not in his Reasons consider, or even make reference to, the testimony of Paul Royce, Gail Wright, or the Blank Agreement.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2 ERRORS IN JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>35. The trial judge erred as follows:
<P1>(a) Erred in law and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Erred in law, and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by failing to properly assess the credibility of the plaintiff and Mr. Wright.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3 ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>The trial judge erred in law and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence</TI>
<P>36. A failure to consider relevant evidence is an error of law reviewable on the standard of correctness.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Morin</SOC><CITE>1992 CanLII 40</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1992] 3 S.C.R. 286</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R.v. J.M.H.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 45</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>37. An appellate court must look at the reasons of the trial judge in their entire context and consider whether the &ldquo;trial judge appears to have seized the critical issues on the trial. If the evidence is contradictory or confusing the appellate court should ask whether the trial judge appears to have dealt with contradictions&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. R.E.M.</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 51</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>38. This court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Mariano v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2010 BCCA 410</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Mariano</EM>] is instructive. While counsel in <EM>Mariano</EM> framed the appeal as an error in the trial judge's assessment of credibility, the court's conclusion that the trial judge &ldquo;did not deal with important contradictions in the evidence, and appears to have misapprehend or ignored parts of the cross-examinations of the plaintiff's witnesses&rdquo; suggest it was more appropriately an appeal for failure to consider relevant evidence and, therefore reviewed on the standard of correctness.</P>
<P>39. In <CASEREF><SOC>Van Mol v. Ashmore</SOC><CITE>1999 BCCA 6</CITE></CASEREF>, this court considered the judge's failure to refer to certain evidence in his reasons:
<QUOTE><P>[13] Sometimes a trial judge may state a piece of evidence in his or her reasons in a way which is clearly incorrect. But much more often the appellant's argument rests on the fact that the trial judge omitted to refer to a piece of evidence that was relevant to a conclusion or finding of fact. <UNDER>Such an omission is not itself an error unless the circumstances are such that the omission must give rise to a reasoned belief that the trial judge must have forgotten, ignored, or misconceived the evidence in a way which affected his or her conclusion.</UNDER> More usually, the omission is only one factor in the overall task facing the Court of Appeal in relation to questions of fact. The task is one which the Court must face, whether the particular evidence is referred to in the trial reasons or not. That task is to decide whether, on the basis of all the evidence, there was a body of evidence which was properly, judicially, and reasonably capable of supporting the conclusion which the trial judge reached.</P>
<P>[Emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The evidence of Paul Royce</TI>
<P>40. Similar to the evidence of John Darch described by the trial judge as neutral, Paul Royce was also a neutral witness with no interest in the outcome of the trial. Paul Royce was familiar with the royalty and the sale of the royalty to Crew Capital Corporation's three shareholders in 1999, because he acted as Crew Capital Corporation's chartered account during the relevant period.</P>
<P>41. Paul Royce testified at trial that he had a conversation with Mr. Wright around the time the royalty was being sold by Crew Capital Corporation about the fact that Mr. Wright wanted to have the royalty recorded in the name of the plaintiff as his nominee:
<QUOTE><P>Q: So what did you mean by that exactly when you say &ldquo;make sure you have it papered&rdquo;?</P>
<P>A: Well, obviously the entitlement and beneficial interest which would be shareholders of Crew Capital, Gerry Wright was one.</P>
<P>Q: Yes?</P>
<P>A: John Darch and Bob Anderson. So they would be getting the, you know, beneficial interest, all other things being equal. <UNDER>So when Gerry mentioned that he wanted to have David Long as his nominee</UNDER>, I said: Well, just make sure that it is papered properly so that if the intent is that you keep the beneficial interest, then there is some paperwork to support that, not withstanding the fact that somebody else's name is on it&rdquo;.</P>
<P>Q: Now, do you know if any paperwork along those lines was ever draw up?</P>
<P>A: I have no knowledge of it being drawn up, but I stressed it to Gerry several times, and by the end he was saying, &ldquo;Yes, it's taken care of.&rdquo;</P>
<P>Q: Did he say anything else with respect to the paperwork?</P>
<P>A: Yes, he said that he has paperwork in his safe. So I said fine, and left it at that.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Tr. Vol. 5, p. 877, l. 42&mdash;p. 878., l. 19</P1>
<P1>See also, Tr. Vol. 5, pp. 869 - 870</P1></P>
<P>42. The &ldquo;paperwork&rdquo; that Mr. Wright told Mr. Royce was in his safe, must have been a reference to the Blank Agreement.</P>
<P>43. In re-examination, Mr. Royce again confirmed that his understanding was that Mr. Long was acting as a nominee:
<QUOTE><P>Q: Mr. Royce, subsequent to that first meeting you had with Mr. Wright in which he described the capacity in which Mr. Long was holding the royalty, whatever that was&mdash;I guess I will ask two questions: Subsequent to that meeting or at that meeting, did you have any understanding as to in what capacity Mr. Long was holding the royalty?</P>
<P>A: Yes, it was going to be as a nominee.</P>
<P>Q: Okay. Now subsequent to that understanding, did you ever receive any information from Mr. Wright which was inconsistent with that?</P>
<P>A: No, I didn't receive any other information.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Tr. Vol. 5, p. 900, ll. 34&ndash;46</P1></P>
<P>44. Mr. Royce's evidence was critical to the appellants' defence at the trial, and yet the trial judge did not even refer to it in his reasons, let alone attempt to reconcile it with his finding that Mr. Wright intended to gift the plaintiff 50% of the Royalty Interest.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The evidence of Gail Wright</TI>
<P>45. As noted above, an important element of the trial's judge's decision that Mr. Wright intended to gift the plaintiff 50% of the Royalty Interest, was his acceptance of the plaintiff's position that Mr. Wright did so in part because he wanted to shelter it from his wife.</P>
<P>46. However, Gail Wright testified at the trial that she was aware of the royalty &ldquo;from day one&rdquo;, and that she had discussed with her husband the fact that Mr. Long held the Royalty Interest as a nominee.
<P1>Tr. Vol. 5, p. 793, l. 46&mdash;p. 798, l. 5</P1></P>
<P>47. Ms. Wright explained that she received the note from Mr. Brazier in May 1999, by going to his office to pick it up and that the Blank Agreement was attached to the note. It was &ldquo;quite normal procedure&rdquo; for her to pick up documents from Mr. Brazier's office for Mr. Wright if he was not home.</P>
<P>48. Ms. Wright was also forwarded a number of emails by Mr. Wright from Fasken Martineau DuMoulin LLP after the firm was retained in 2006 and paid some of the firm's accounts. Those emails made it clear that the Royalty Interest was registered in the plaintiff's name.
<P1>Tr. Vol. 5, p. 806, l. 6&mdash;p. 811, l. 19</P1></P>
<P>49. All of Ms. Wright's evidence was extremely relevant and went to the critical issue of whether Mr. Wright was attempting to shelter the Royalty Interest from her, but the trial judge did not even make reference to her evidence in his reasons.</P>
<P>50. Moreover, there is no indication as to whether he accepted or rejected her evidence that she had been told by Mr. Wright that the plaintiff held the royalty solely as a nominee. Even if the trial judge rejected that evidence, at a minimum it was still incumbent on him to explain how he came to the conclusion that Mr. Wright initially intended to shelter the Royalty Interest from Ms. Wright, in light of the fact that she received a copy of the Blank Agreement directly from Mr. Brazier.</P>
<P>51. If Mr. Wright's intent was to hide the Royalty Interest from Ms. Wright, it is utterly implausible that he would have only a few months after transferring the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff allowed Mr. Brazier to provide Ms. Wright with the Blank Document evidencing that the Royalty Interest was held by the plaintiff.</P>
<P>52. This is a contradiction that the trial judge was obliged to explain.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Paragon Capital Corp. v. Morgan</SOC><CITE>2014 ABCA 363</CITE><PARANUM>48</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Sheppard</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 26</CITE><PARANUM>15, 28</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>53. It is respectfully submitted that the critical nature of Mr. Royce and Ms. Wright's evidence, must give rise to a reasonable belief that the trial judge must have forgotten, ignored, or misconceived their evidence in a way that affected his conclusion.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The trial judge erred in law and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by failing to properly assess the credibility of the plaintiff and Mr. Wright</TI>
<P>54. The plaintiff's position at trial was that the February 1999 transfer of the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff was 50% a gift. Accordingly, the presumption of resulting trust applies to this case, and the burden of proof was on the plaintiff, on a balance of probabilities, to displace the presumption that Mr. Wright did not intend to gift the plaintiff a portion of the Royalty Interest.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fuller v. Harper</SOC><CITE>2010 BCCA 421</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Pecore v. Pecore</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 17</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Pecore</EM>]</P1></P>
<P>55. In considering the intention of the transferor, it was necessary that the trial judge consider whether the &ldquo;transferor had any rational purpose for the transfer other than a gift&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Pecore</EM> at paras. 45&ndash;47</P1></P>
<P>56. It appears that the trial judge considered the evidence of the plaintiff to be more probable for three main reasons:
<P1>(a) The gift of 50% of the Royalty Interest was consistent with the past friendship and financial business relationship of the parties;</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Darch corroborated the plaintiff's assertion that Mr. Wright initially preferred a &ldquo;better a half than ultimately a quarter interest in the royalty&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c)Mr. Wright is a sophisticated businessman, and could have effected a private declaration of trust document between himself and Mr. Long.</P1></P>
<P>57. With respect, all three reasons are contradicted by the evidence at trial. First, the consistent evidence at the trial was that to the extent Mr. Wright and the plaintiff had a business relationship, it was on the basis that Mr. Wright invested in the business and the plaintiff would <UNDER>earn</UNDER> his 50% by way of sweat equity. There was no evidence at the trial of Mr. Wright gifting the plaintiff shares of any companies the plaintiff was not involved in.</P>
<P>58. The trial judge's finding at paragraph 30 of his reasons that the gift of 50% of the Royalty Interest was &ldquo;entirely consistent with ventures [Mr. Wright and the plaintiff] engaged in in the past&rdquo; has no support in the evidence, and is contrary to his own finding at paragraph 28 that the business relationship between them was such that Mr. Wright funded the business and Mr. Long operated them.</P>
<P>59. The royalty was earned through the efforts of the three shareholders of Crew Capital Corporation and the plaintiff had nothing to do with it.</P>
<P>60. Second, the assertion that Mr. Wright was gaining a &ldquo;half&rdquo; rather than a &ldquo;quarter interest in the royalty&rdquo; by sheltering it from his wife, does not make sense and is also not supported by the evidence. If Mr. Wright really was seeking to shelter the Royalty Interest from his wife, he was not gaining anything by then gifting 50% of the Royalty Interest to the plaintiff. In effect, the plaintiff simply stepped into Ms. Wright's shoes.</P>
<P>61. In addition, the plaintiff testified that if the Royalty Interest began to generate revenue while he held it, he would have reported 100% of the revenue to his country's tax authorities and presumably then would have paid taxes in Ireland on the proceeds. Mr. Wright would not have therefore reaped any tax savings by gifting the plaintiff a 50% interest.
<P1>Tr. Vol. 1, p. 183, ll. 8&ndash;38</P1></P>
<P>62. Third, while it is correct that Mr. Wright did not effect a private declaration of trust document, he did &ldquo;properly paper&rdquo; and protect his interests by causing the plaintiff to enter into the Blank Agreement. The Blank Agreement gave Mr. Wright the ability to transfer the royalty to another entity at any time.</P>
<P>63. Moreover, the trial judge did not explain why the fact that Mr. Wright did not &ldquo;leave a traceable paper trail about the true nature of the transfer&rdquo; made the plaintiff's version of events more probable. The trial judge accepted that it was reasonable for the plaintiff to trust Mr. Wright at his word based on their long personal and professional relationship at paragraph 36 of his reasons, and there was no reason for the trial judge not to accept that Mr. Wright equally trusted the plaintiff.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4 NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>64. That this appeal be allowed and that judgement be entered in favour of the appellants.</P>
<P>65. In the alternative, that there be a new trial on all of the issues.</P>
<P>66. Costs in favour of the appellant in this Court and the Court below.</P>
<P>67. Such further and other relief as to this Honourable Court may seem just and meet.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</P>
