<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>In the words of the learned trial judge, the primary issue faced in this action was the &ldquo;conflicting credibility between the parties as to their agreed arrangement.&rdquo;</P>
<P>While, the appellants, Gerald Wright and Red Branch Investments Ltd., allege that the trial judge committed palpable and overriding errors by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence, there is simply no basis for this allegation.</P>
<P>The trial of this action involved the testimony of 8 witnesses, 5 for the plaintiff and 3 for the defendants, and required 14 days to be heard, with an additional day for special costs. The witnesses were all subject to extensive cross examination and counsel gave substantive closing submissions in both oral and written form. The trial judge reserved for almost two months and, while his reasons are brief, they dealt with the single most important issue at trial, being the credibility of the two main witnesses, David Long and Gerald Wright.</P>
<P>In the end, after considering all of the evidence, the trial judge found that Mr. Long's version of events was more believable than that of Mr. Wright and, accordingly, he found in favour of the plaintiff. In finding for the plaintiff, the trial judge gave his reasons for preferring the evidence of Mr. Long over that of Mr. Wright. While he did not expressly say so, by implication, the trial judge rejected the evidence of Mr. Wright's wife, Gail Wright, and did not consider the evidence of Paul Royce to be determinative of the findings, especially in light of the trial judge's finding in the special costs hearing that Mr. Wright was capable of putting forward a &ldquo;self-serving story&rdquo;.</P>
<P>In short, there were no errors in judgment on the part of the trial judge, let alone palpable and overriding errors. Instead, in this appeal, the appellants are seeking to have this Honourable Court substitute its discretion in the place of the trial judge without any basis to do so.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. Long and Wright were long-time friends and business partners, having met in Belfast in 1974.
<P1>Appellants' Appeal Record (&ldquo;<BOLD>AAR</BOLD>&rdquo;), Reasons for Judgment, paras. 1 and 13</P1></P>
<P>2. Wright, Darch and Bob Anderson were each one third shareholders in Crew, as well as directors and officers of the company.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 9</P1></P>
<P>3. Crew owned the Royalty which was a 1.5% (of 75%) royalty interest in a potash mine which had yet to be developed in Thailand by Asia Pacific.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 8</P1></P>
<P>4. In August 1996, Wright and Long incorporated two companies in Ireland of which they are both directors, being Dublin Direct Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Dublin Direct</BOLD>&rdquo;) and Norvan Holdings Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Norvan</BOLD>&rdquo;). Wright and Long were equal shareholders in Norvan. In turn, Norvan owned all of the shares of Dublin Direct and, subsequently, Dublin Sports Caf&ea; Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Dublin Sports Caf&ea;</BOLD>&rdquo;), which owned and operated the Pub. Wright always provided the funding for these various business ventures, some of which was significant.
<P1>Transcript Extract Book of the Respondent (&ldquo;<BOLD>TEB</BOLD>&rdquo;) Tab 1, pp. 16 to 19, ll. 3&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1-2</P1>
<P1>TEB Tab 2, pp. 21 to 23, ll. 40&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;32</P1></P>
<P>5. In January 1998, a location was secured for the Pub, and a lease was signed in April that year. Construction on the Pub started shortly thereafter and it began operations on October 22, 1998. Wright had no operational involvement in the Pub. While Dublin Sports Caf&ea; paid his living expenses in Dublin, at no time was Long able to draw a salary from the Pub. Long struggled to keep the Pub operational until it was forced into liquidation on October 17, 2003.
<P1>TEB Tab 3, pp. 31 to 35, ll. 44&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;13</P1></P>
<P>6. On November 4, 1997, the directors of Crew determined that they did not want to leave the Royalty in the company anymore, and decided that each of them would purchase a one-third share of it for $13,333. Despite the fact that the sale had not taken place, Crew reported the sale of the Royalty to the Shareholders to CRA during its February 28, 1998 fiscal period.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 10</P1></P>
<P>7. In [date omitted], Bob Anderson died unexpectedly.</P>
<P>8. On or about February 16, 1999, Crew received the Opinion which explained how best to deal with the various tax issues that could arise due to the reported sale of the Royalty to CRA. There were two options provided in the Opinion, being to consider the sale of the Royalty to the Shareholders null and void as it had not been paid for, or to leave the sale of the Royalty as it was and buttress the facts surrounding the sale in the Royalty Agreement. The second option was the one that Crew opted to follow.
<P1>TEB Tab 37, pp. 889 to 890, ll. 14&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;22</P1>
<P1>Appellants' Appeal Book (&ldquo;<BOLD>AAB</BOLD>&rdquo;) pp. 96&ndash;99, Exhibit 1, Tab 20</P1></P>
<P>9. It was agreed by the external accountant for Crew at the time, Paul Royce (&ldquo;<BOLD>Royce</BOLD>&rdquo;), and Darch that the Opinion was the catalyst for the Royalty Agreement and the promissory notes referred to therein, as well as the date selected for the purchase of the Royalty. Royce's evidence was that Wright was in the meeting with Mr. Voyer for the purpose of preparing the Opinion. On cross examination, contrary to the evidence of Darch and Royce, Wright denied that the Opinion had anything to do with the steps that were followed or that he had any involvement with it.
<P1>TEB Tab 35, pp. 872 to 873, ll. 20&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;4</P1>
<P1>TEB Tab 19, pp. 618 to 622, ll. 9&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;41</P1>
<P1>TEB Tab 20, pp. 625 to 626, ll. 11&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;21</P1></P>
<P>10. According to Long, he was contacted by Wright in February 1999, about the Royalty. During this conversation Wright told Long that he was sending him over some papers, being the Royalty Agreement and Promissory Note, that he needed Long to sign and return them as soon as possible, and that he would send the funds required to complete the sale under the Royalty Agreement. Long agreed, signing and returning the Royalty Agreement and Promissory Note.
<P1>TEB Tab 4, pp. 43 to 45, ll. 40&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;22</P1></P>
<P>11. By way of a personal cheque dated February 19, 1999, Wright caused $15,000 to be taken from his own personal CIBC account, and not the joint HSBC account that he shared with Mrs. Wright, to be deposited into the account of his own personal corporation Cypress. Despite the evidence of Mrs. Wright that she would take care of all accounts on behalf of the Wrights and their businesses, the payment was effected by Wright leaving a pre-signed cheque for Peter Wong, the company accountant, and not Mrs. Wright. Mr. Wong then, in turn, caused Cypress to wire $15,073.30 to Long on this same day. Long subsequently wired $14,310 (the amount wired to him less exchange rates and handling fees) to Crew for payment of the Royalty.
<P1>TEB Tab 7, pp. 543 to 546, ll. 46-47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;11</P1></P>
<P>12. Both Wright and Royce confirmed that Crew received the funds from Long for the payment of the Royalty.
<P1>TEB Tab 6, pp. 543 to 545, ll. 43&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;31</P1>
<P1>TEB Tab 38, pp. 894 to 895, ll. 45&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;29</P1></P>
<P>13. Of note, it was the evidence of Mrs. Wright that, in 1999, all family money was held in a joint account with HSBC and that their &ldquo;personal accounts&rdquo;, as a general rule, had nothing in them. Wright would leave signed blank cheques for Mrs. Wright with Cypress in case there was something that Wright wanted put through in his absence as she was paying bills and keeping everything organized.
<P1>TEB Tab 27, pp. 791 to 792, ll. 27&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;24</P1></P>
<P>14. Mrs. Wright was not involved in any way in the transferring of funds to Long on February 19, 1999. In fact, on cross examination, Mrs. Wright's evidence was that Wright &ldquo;probably&rdquo; still had an account with CIBC in 1999 but that it was &ldquo;never used.&rdquo; When confronted with the CIBC cheque, she changed her evidence to say that it did not matter since she was responsible for all the accounts, but then admitted that it was not her writing on the cheque which was used to transfer the funds to Cypress nor did she attend at the bank to wire the funds to Long. In addition, after claiming that she did all the bookkeeping for their family and their companies, Mrs. Wright further admitted that the bookkeeping entry for this payment was not done in her writing. Most telling, however, was her flat out denial that the funds which were sent on that date were sent to Long to pay for the Royalty and that the Royalty was paid directly by Cypress to Crew. In her words this &ldquo;definitely&rdquo; did not happen and Long definitely did not send the funds to Crew for the purchase of the Royalty.
<P1>TEB Tab 30, pp. 840 to 842, ll. 9&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;42</P1></P>
<P>15. Wright confirmed that Mrs. Wright would have had the ability to undertake this transaction to Long but, instead, he asked Mr. Wong to deal with it.
<P1>TEB Tab 26, pp. 740 to 741, ll. 27&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;40</P1></P>
<P>16. Around the same time as the Royalty was being purchased, Wright also caused a condominium to be purchased in Bangkok in the name of Ms. Sanksuwan. He told Mrs. Wright that Ms. Sanksuwan was a &ldquo;friend&rdquo; and &ldquo;business associate&rdquo;, and that it was being put into her name to help with the mortgage. He did not tell Mrs. Wright of the nature of his relationship with Ms. Sanksuwan, that she was living in the condominium full time or that she stayed in it with him when he was in Thailand.
<P1>TEB Tab 29, pp. 838 to 839, ll. 15&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;46</P1></P>
<P>17. The purchase of the Royalty was finally effected by way of the Royalty Agreement in late February 1999, but backdated to November 1997 in order to prevent estate issues arising from Mr. Anderson's death. Wright placed his share of the Royalty into Long's name.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, paras. 11 through 13</P1></P>
<P>18. Despite the fact that the Royalty Agreement was not entered into until late February 1999, it was the evidence of Mrs. Wright that she would have placed this signed agreement into their safe in their home in West Vancouver in November 1997, more than a year and a half before it was signed.
<P1>TEB Tab 28, p. 795, ll. 11&ndash;16</P1></P>
<P>19. According to Long, whose evidence was accepted by the trial judge as fact, Wright placed the Royalty in Long's name, having gifted Long a 50% beneficial interest in this asset and holding the other half for the benefit of Wright. According to Long, Wright told him that he would rather gift half of the Royalty to Long than pay half to CRA and then share the remaining half with Mrs. Wright, whom he was planning to leave at the time.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 15</P1></P>
<P>20. Darch, an independent witness with no vested interest in this litigation, confirmed that Wright had also told him around this time that he intended to leave Mrs. Wright for Ms. Sanksuwan, and that he had gifted half of the beneficial interest in the Royalty to Long as he would &ldquo;rather receive a half than a quarter&rdquo; after he paid taxes to CRA, and settled out in a divorce with Mrs. Wright. Darch warned Wright on several occasions to properly document this transaction.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, paras. 47, 48 and 50</P1></P>
<P>21. According to Wright, whose evidence was rejected by the trial judge, he placed the Royalty into Long's name as a mere nominee and was held in trust by Long for the 100% beneficial interest of Wright.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 16</P1></P>
<P>22. According to Long, in April or May 1999, Wright came to visit him in Belfast with Ms. Sanksuwan, advising Long that he had married Ms. Sanksuwan in a Thai wedding ceremony. Wright advised Long that he was planning to leave Mrs. Wright and move to Thailand with Ms. Sanksuwan. During this visit, Wright asked Long to sign the Blank Transfer Agreement in case he needed to move the Royalty quickly.
<P1>TEB Tab 5, pp. 50&ndash;53, ll. 22&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;35</P1></P>
<P>23. It was the evidence of Royce that Wright told him that he intended to move to Thailand in the future.
<P1>TEB Tab 34, p. 870, ll. 25&ndash;33</P1></P>
<P>24. While it was the evidence of Mrs. Wright that she picked up a &ldquo;corrected&rdquo; version of the Blank Transfer Agreement from George Brazier (&ldquo;<BOLD>Brazier</BOLD>&rdquo;), then counsel for Crew, this evidence was not accepted by the plaintiff and was subject to vigorous cross examination. There was no independent evidence outside of the testimony of Mrs. Wright that she picked up the Blank Transfer Agreement in May 1999. In fact, the evidence of Mrs. Wright was not supported by document production provided by the Defendants as the document appended to this note in the Defendants' production was a corrected version of the Royalty Agreement which named Long as the owner of the Royalty. Of note, Brazier was not called as a witness at trial.
<P1>TEB Tab 31, pp. 843 to 847, ll. 8&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;22</P1></P>
<P>25. It was the evidence of Wright that the Blank Transfer Agreement was signed by Long in July 1999 and that Long continued to hold the Royalty on behalf of himself for 11 years, until June 2010, at which time Wright asked him to transfer the entirety of it to Red Branch, a company owned and controlled by Wright and his family in Hong Kong.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 17</P1></P>
<P>26. In 2006, Asia Pacific was sold to a Thai national company, Italia Thai. Darch wanted to ensure that Italia Thai would honour the Royalty Agreement and, as a result, he contacted Wright to discuss hiring legal counsel to deal with the matter. Wright agreed and on April 26, 2006, he had Long sign a letter authorizing Wright to act as his agent in relation to the Royalty (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Agency Letter</BOLD>&rdquo;).
<P1>AAB p. 149, Exhibit 1, Tab 38</P1></P>
<P>27. Legal counsel were initially retained by Darch and Wright to insure that Italia Thai honoured the Royalty Agreement. Alice Anderson was later included in this arrangement. At all times, Long was named as the client and Wright was said to be Long's authorized agent. At no time did Wright advise the other Royalty holders or legal counsel that he was the beneficial owner of the Royalty or that Long was a mere nominee. Instead, Wright made the following representations:
<P1>a. On April 25, 2006, he drafted the Agency Letter in which Long was noted as the registered holder of the Royalty and in which he appointed Wright as his:
<QUOTE><P>Agent, with full authority to act on my behalf, in all matters relating to this Royalty. (AAB p. 149, Exhibit 1, Tab 38).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>b. He wrote to David Anderson on April 25, 2006, stating:
<QUOTE><P>The Royalty interest was subsequently sold by Crew Capital Corp. to Bob, John and myself (0.5% each), personally, and since then these interests [sic] have been assigned, equally, to one of John's private holding companies, an overseas business acquaintance of mine (Mr. David Long) and to Bob's estate... I confirm that I act as Agent for Mr. Long and have the authority to appoint you as his representative in this matter. (AAB pp. 152-153, Exhibit 1, Tab 40).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>Of note, both Darch's company and Bob Anderson's estate had legal and beneficial ownership of their shares of the Royalty.</P1>
<P1>c. In his May 2, 2006 email to Mark Andrews, QC, Wright stated:
<QUOTE><P>Crew Capital Corp subsequently sold the Royalty interest to Bob, John and myself (0.5% each), personally and, since then, these interests have been assigned, equally to one of John's private holding companies, to Bob Anderson's estate and to an overseas business acquaintance of mine, Mr. David Long (I confirm that I am authorized to act as Agent for Mr. Long in this matter).</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>The Royalty holders feel that their interests are threatened by the takeover and the intent of the purchasers to convert Asia Pacific to a private, non-reporting company. (AAB pp. 163-164, Exhibit 1, Tab 46).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>d. Also on May 2, 2006, Wright stated as follows to Darch:
<QUOTE><P>Incidentally, David Long has given me written authority to act on his behalf, and he will be responsible for his part of the costs. I'll keep him fully informed and, if Mark needs anything from him, I'll arrange it. (AAB v. 1, pp. 168&ndash;170, Exhibit 1, Tab 50).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>e. On May 8, 2006, Wright forwarded the Agency Letter to Mr. Andrews, QC, (AAB v. 1, p. 149, Exhibit 1, Tab 38) by email (AAB v. 2, p. 759, Exhibit 9). In this email he wrote:
<QUOTE><P>PS. For your info. I attach a letter from Mr. David Long, one of the Royalty holders, appointing me as his Agent. David, aho [sic] is a close business associate of mine, acquired the Royalty from Crew Capital Corp in 1999.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>f. The June 28, 2006 retainer letter from Fasken Martineau notes Long as their client and provides that Wright is acting as Long's agent. It also confirms Wright's guarantee to pay Long's portion of the legal fees. Wright was responsible for keeping Long informed. Again, there is no mention of Wright having any beneficial interest in the Royalty (AAB, v. 1, pp. 216&ndash;220, Exhibit 1, Tab 65). This retainer letter was forwarded to Wright to forward to Long (AAB, v. 1, pp. 221&ndash;225, Exhibit 1, Tab 66), which Wright did (AAB, v. 1, pp. 63&ndash;69, Exhibit 1, Tabs 68 and 69).</P1>
<P1>g. On July 14, 2006, Mr. Wright wrote:
<QUOTE><P>I gather that David Long has already signed and sent you the Representation Letter. When we meet, I'll also sign it and deliver the requested retainer on Mr. Long's behalf. ...</P>
<P>We should not expose the Royalty holders to a taxation regime which they are not familiar with or, presently, subject to. Each of the Royalty Holders will have their own taxation treatment depending upon their tax domicile. (AAB, v. 1, pp. 235-236, Exhibit 1, Tab 70).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>h. On August 18, 2006, Wright wrote:
<QUOTE><P>Regarding the tax issue, I don't think John's willingness to accept royalty payments in Canada net of the withholding tax deals with the issue. [...] Also, David Long (or his personal company) is not a Canadian taxpayer and does not feel that agreeing to a 15%, probably non-recoverable, withholding tax is the best way to deal with the situation. (AAB, v. 1, pp. 72&ndash;78, Exhibit 1, Tabs 78 and 79)</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>i. On August 21, 2006, Wright responded to tax advice obtained by Darch as follows:
<QUOTE><P>thanks for the tax info. from M. Butters. I note the existence of a tax treaty between Thailand and the UK. Unfortunately D. Long is a resident of the Republic of Ireland at the moment, but I'm sure he can consider reorganizing the domicile for the royalty interest if there is a benefit in doing so. (AAB, v. 1, pp. 278&ndash;280, Exhibit 1, Tab 84).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>j. On August 23, 2006, Wright received an email from Long asking about &ldquo;the new royalty agreement&rdquo; that was being referred to in emails that he was receiving from Mr. Darch. (AAB, v. 1, pp. 294-295, Exhibit 1, Tab 88). Wright responded:
<QUOTE><P>The &lsquo;new&rsquo; Royalty agreement refers to the change in ownership and the recognition of the present agreement. The Thai company wants to wrap up APR and hold the assets in Thailand, so we are replacing the APR agreement with one from the Thai company, on the same general terms. Naturally, each side is &lsquo;covering its ass&rsquo; as much as is reasonable. One negative, from my viewpoint, is that revenues will be reduced by a 15% withholding tax on funds remitted from Thailand, but it's better to tighten up the agreement at this point rather than have to get the lawyers involved later.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>k. On November 9, 2006, Wright wrote:
<QUOTE><P>Incidentally, David Long does intend to assign his portion of the royalty to a private (European) holding company. It may be more convenient, given that the agreement is not yet finalized, that this company should be a party to the agreement rather than David? (AAB, v. 1, pp. 304&ndash;308, Exhibit 1, Tab 93).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>l. On December 13, 2006, Mr. Gabrielson asked Wright to which address he should forward the signed Royalty agreement (AAB, v. 1, p. 393, Exhibit 1, Tab 104). Wright responded by giving Mr. Gabrielson Long's address as opposed to his own, despite his evidence that he kept all important information relating to the Royalty in his safe in his house in West Vancouver.</P1>
<P1>m. On March 23, 2007, Wright emailed Mr. Wang and provided:
<QUOTE><P>my name is Gerry Wright and I have been involved with the proposed Sin Rae royalty agreement on behalf of my associate, Mr. David Long, <UNDER>one of the three Asia Pacific Royalty holders</UNDER>. [...] I recently attended a Vancouver meeting with the lawyers for the Royalty holders, as well as one of the other Royalty holders (Mr. John Darch, a former associate of mine) and I think it may be useful to have an information meeting with you. (AAB, v. 2, p. 762, Exhibit 10, emphasis added).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>n. On March 27, 2007, Wright emailed Darch with respect to meeting with Mr. Wang and provided:
<QUOTE><P>I'm leaving Bangkok tomorrow, for Dublin, and will meet with David Long on Friday. (AAB, v. 2, p. 763, Exhibit 11).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>o. On July 2, 2007, when it looked like the matter might be going to litigation, Wright wrote:
<QUOTE><P>However, neither David Long or I relish significant legal costs, unless there is no alternative to Court action. (AAB, v. 2, pp. 396&ndash;403, Exhibit 1, Tab 107).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>p. On November 24, 2009, Wright wrote to Mr. Gabrielson, after receiving email correspondence from Darch and stated:
<QUOTE><P>Incidentally, David Long will be assigning his royalty interest to a third party, a private company registered in Hong Kong. I shall arrange for David to provide you with a copy of the assignment agreement so that the finalized documents can include the new <UNDER>beneficial</UNDER> holder rather than David. (AAB, v. 2, p. 472, Exhibit 2, Tab 121, emphasis added).</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>q. On November 29, 2009, Wright wrote to Mr. Gabrielson to provide:
<QUOTE><P>David Long has asked me to provide details of the assignment of his royalty interest to a Hong Kong company. [...] David will confirm the assignment and provide you with a copy of the assignment agreement, shortly. (AAB, v. 2, p. 473, Exhibit 2, Tab 122).</P></QUOTE></P1></P>
<P>28. It was the evidence of Long, which was accepted by the trial judge, that in June 2010 Long was asked to sign the Red Branch Transfer Agreement and, at the time that he signed this Agreement, Wright expressly made the following representations to him:
<P1>(a) That he was the beneficial owner of Red Branch and that he controlled the company;</P1>
<P1>(b) That the reason he wanted to transfer the Royalty was because there were tax advantages to both Long and himself to having the Royalty held by a Hong Kong company; and,</P1>
<P1>(c) That Red Branch would continue to hold the Royalty in trust for both Long and Wright as before, with each of them having an equal beneficial interest and, as a result, he would make Long a 50% shareholder and director of Red Branch.
<P2>AAR, Reasons, para. 19</P2></P1></P>
<P>29. According to Long, given their lifelong friendship and business relationship that had been shared between them, Long trusted Wright and agreed to sign the Red Branch Transfer Agreement for $1.00, which agreement was dated for reference September 1, 2009. The trial judge accepted that this type of arrangement was typical as between Long and Wright and that Long trusted Wright to follow through with his promise. While he was not immediately made an officer and director of Red Branch, Long had complete faith that Wight would honour his representations.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, paras. 20 to 22</P1></P>
<P>30. The objective evidence showed that, consistent with Long's understanding and the representations that were said to have been made, in May 2011, Wright provided Long with confidential information related to the Royalty. It was the further accepted evidence of Long that shortly after Wright sent him this email, Wright discussed the contents of it with him at length when they met later that month.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 23</P1>
<P1>AAB, v. 2, pp. 586&ndash;589, Exhibit 2, Tab 144</P1></P>
<P>31. It was only after his falling out with Wright at the end of June 2011, that Long began to question whether or not Wright would honour their agreement and insure that Red Branch held half of the Royalty in trust for him. As a result, in January 2012, a demand was made of Red Branch to confirm this fact. Red Branch refused to acknowledge this trust and, as a result, the within action was commenced.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, paras. 45 and 46</P1>
<P1>AAB, v. 2, pp. 684-685, Exhibit 2, Tab 190</P1></P>
<P>32. The plaintiff tendered evidence from four independent and neutral witnesses with no financial interest in the outcome of the litigation, being Darch, David Anderson, Mr. Andrews, QC, and Mr. Gabrielson.</P>
<P>33. Darch's key evidence was as follows:
<P1>(a) He was a long time business associate of Wright and a fellow Royalty holder. He testified that Wright told him that he was appointing Long as his nominee and he was sharing his share of the Royalty with Long as he would rather receive half of the Royalty than lose half to CRA and share the other half with Mrs. Wright, whom he was planning to leave for his Thai mistress. According to Darch, Wright told him this on more than one occasion.</P1>
<P1>(b) He advised Wright that if he was going to transfer legal ownership of the Royalty to Long that he should &ldquo;properly paper the transaction&rdquo; in order to avoid a future dispute about the actual extent of Long's interest in the Royalty. Wright advised that he had &ldquo;already taken care of the matter.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(c) The original Royalty Agreement was entered into in February 1999, and the Agreement was back-dated due to the untimely death of Bob Anderson.
<P2>AAR, Reasons, paras. 47 to 50</P2></P1></P>
<P>34. David Anderson's key evidence was as follows:
<P1>(a) He is a lawyer and the brother of the late Bob Anderson. He represented Alice Anderson with respect to the Royalty.</P1>
<P1>(b) Alice Anderson was asked to participate in the amended Royalty Agreement with Italia Thai even though she did not contribute to the legal bills that were issued by Fasken Martineau in relation to same.</P1>
<P1>(c) Based upon communications received from Wright, Dave Anderson's understanding was that Long owned the Royalty and that Wright was acting as Long's agent.
<P2>AAR, Reasons, paras. 51 and 52</P2></P1></P>
<P>35. With respect to Mr. Andrews, QC, and Mr. Gabrielson, the trial judge considered the fact that their evidence, as lawyers, was that until the Royalty was transferred to Red Branch they believed Mr. Long to be the owner of said Royalty, and that Wright was acting as his agent. Despite the fact that Wright was instructing them, at no time did he advise them that he held a beneficial ownership in the Royalty.
<P1>AAR, Reasons, para. 53</P1></P>
<P>36. As part of their case, the Defendants called Royce, who is a personal friend of the Wrights, was the accountant for Crew and continues to be the accountant for the Wrights. Royce's evidence in direct was as follows:
<P1>(a) When Wright told him he was going to put the Royalty into Long's name, that he told Wright if he intended to keep the benefit of the Royalty then he needed to make sure that he had the paperwork in place to satisfy that he maintained that beneficial interest;</P1>
<P1>(b) When asked specifically whether or not he understood Long to have a beneficial interest in the Royalty, he told Wright that if he intended to retain the beneficial interest in the Royalty then he should make sure that he papered it in such a way that anyone looking at it would say that it might be in Long's name but that Wright had the beneficial interest in it;</P1>
<P1>(c) Wright advised him that he was intending to live offshore in Thailand and that he was tax driven to put it in someone else's name; and,</P1>
<P1>(d) When he counseled Wright to get the paperwork done, Wright told him that he would &ldquo;take care of it&rdquo; but Mr. Royce was never privy to this documentation.
<P2>TEB Tab 33, pp. 869 to 871, ll. 42&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;14</P2></P1></P>
<P>37. On cross examination, Royce confirmed that Wright told him that he was putting the Royalty in Long's name and that he told him if he intended to keep the beneficial interest then this should be put in writing. There were no further details provided other than Wright telling him that it was taken care of and in his safe.
<P1>TEB Tab 39, p. 895, ll. 30&ndash;41</P1></P>
<P>38. Royce's further evidence was that if Wright was the beneficial owner of the Royalty, he would have been obligated to report the disposition of the Royalty to Red Branch in the tax year when it was done. But Wright did not do this.
<P1>TEB Tab 40, pp. 897 to 898, ll. 13&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;20</P1></P>
<P>39. In re-examination Royce was asked a leading question by counsel for the defendants that incorrectly summarized his evidence, stating that Wright had told him that Long would be acting as his nominee. It was only after being asked this leading question that Royce stated he had been told this.
<P1>TEB Tab 41, pp. 900 to 901, ll. 9&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;3</P1></P>
<P>40. Even if Royce's evidence could be accepted that Wright had told him that Long was a nominee, as set out above, Wright told other parties, including Darch and counsel at Fasken Martineau, that Long was the owner of the Royalty and that he had a beneficial interest.</P>
<P>41. Mrs. Wright was not an independent witness and has the same vested interest as Wright in this litigation.</P>
<P>42. There were no other witnesses called by the Defendants in the trial of this action.</P>
<P>43. In choosing to accept Long's version of events, the trial judge provided the following reasons:
<P1>(a) That the representation of a beneficial 50:50 share of the Royalty was consistent with the past friendship and financial business relationships between Long and Wright;</P1>
<P1>(b) That, despite being warned about &ldquo;properly papering&rdquo; the nature of the shared Royalty arrangement with Long, Wright chose not to leave a paper trail, ostensibly for personal domestic and taxation reasons and Darch corroborated the reasons provided by Long; and,</P1>
<P1>(c) Even though Wright is a sophisticated and experienced businessman, he chose not to leave a traceable paper trail about the true nature of the transfer, being concerned about potential taxation consequences if the true nature of the transfer was papered. Despite this, he did not effect a private declaration of trust document between himself and Long.
<P2>AR, Reasons, para. 57</P2></P1></P>
<P>44. The credibility of the parties and their various witnesses was the subject of substantial argument in closing submissions.
<P1>Respondent's Appeal Book (&ldquo;<BOLD>RAB</BOLD>&rdquo;) pgs. 7&ndash;53, Written Submissions of the Plaintiff</P1>
<P1>RAB pgs. 54&ndash;70, Outline of Submissions of the Defendants</P1>
<P1>RAB pgs. 71&ndash;76, Reply Submissions of the Plaintiff</P1></P>
<P>45. On February 9, 2016, after having obtained judgment, Long applied for special costs. In granting same, the trial judge specifically held as follows:
<P1>(a) That the pre-litigation conduct of the Defendants was unconscionable and in the nature of fraud.</P1>
<P1>(b) That after gifting 50 percent of the Royalty to Long and then later persuading Long to transfer his ownership to Red Branch on an express oral trust basis, Wright reneged on the agreement and denied the existence of Long's beneficial interest, which breached the fiduciary duty of the defendants and was a fraud.</P1>
<P1>(c) That during the trial Wright continued his deceit by alleging that Long commenced the within action as a means of revenge and to engage on a campaign of harassment against him, necessitating a protraction of the litigation and added unnecessary time and expense to the trial by alleging a defence without merit and an obfuscation of the major issue: was there a created trust and a breach thereof.</P1>
<P1>(d) That at trial much time was spent casting aspersions on Long's character going to his overall credibility.</P1>
<P1>(e) That he put forward a self-serving story that Long's involvement in the transaction was only as a convenient favour for Wright without beneficial interest and that this story when coupled with the character aspersions was reprehensible.
<P2>RAB pgs. 3&ndash;6, Oral Ruling, paras. 5 and 6</P2></P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ERRORS IN JUDGMENT OR ISSUES ON APPEAL</TI>
<P>46. The appellants allege that the trial judge erred as follows:
<P1>(a) That he erred in law and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence; and,</P1>
<P1>(b) That he erred in law, and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by failing to properly assess the credibility of Long and Wright.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>ISSUE 1</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Alleged Failure to Consider Evidence</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Law:</UNDER></TI>
<P>47. The appellants argue that the trial judge erred in law and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence.</P>
<P>48. Of note, at paragraph 36 of their factum, the appellants argue that a failure to consider relevant evidence is an error of law reviewable on the standard of correctness, and cites two criminal cases, namely <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Morin</SOC><CITE>[1992] 3 SCR 286</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. J.M.H.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 45</CITE></CASEREF>. With all respect to the appellants, their analysis of these cases is simply not correct. The above cases deal with appeals commenced by crown counsel to overturn acquittals, and the specific requirements of section 676(1)(a) of the Criminal Code of Canada, which provides that acquittals may only be overturned on an error of law. The analysis of appeal courts when specifically considering evidence in relation to the <EM>Code</EM> do not apply in a civil case. Instead, the issue before this honourable court is whether or not the trial judge made palpable and overriding errors of fact in his trial judgment.
<P1>Respondent's Book of Authorities (&ldquo;<BOLD>BOA</BOLD>&rdquo;) Tab 8, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Morin</SOC><CITE>[1992] 3 SCR 386</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>BOA Tab 7, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. J.M.H.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 45</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>49. With respect the appellants' assertion that there was a presumption of resulting trust that ought to have been applied by the trial judge, with all respect, this is not the case either. While the trial judge is to commence his inquiry with the applicable presumption in mind, he is then to weigh all of the evidence in an attempt to ascertain, on a balance of probabilities, the transferor's actual intention. The presumption is only determinative of the result where there is insufficient evidence to rebut it on a balance of probabilities.
<P1>BOA Tab 6, <CASEREF><SOC>Pecore v. Pecore</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 17</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>50. It is only if the trial judge cannot ascertain the actual intention of the transferor that he is entitled to rely on the presumption of resulting trust.
<P1>BOA Tab 3, <CASEREF><SOC>Fuller v. Fuller Estate</SOC><CITE>2010 BCCA 421</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>51. The factual findings of the trial judge with which the appellants take issue are entitled to deference absent a palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>52. A trial judge's findings of fact are deserving of great deference:
<QUOTE><P>The trial judge is better situated to make factual findings owing to his or her extensive exposure to the evidence, the advantage of hearing testimony viva voce, and the judge's familiarity with the case as a whole. Because the primary role of the trial judge is to weigh and assess voluminous quantities of evidence, the expertise and insight of the trial judge in this area should be respected.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>BOA Tab 5, <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>53. The Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Housen</EM> emphasized that, where there is evidence to support a conclusion, a difference of opinion over the weight to be assigned to the evidence does not provide a proper foundation for an appellate court to interfere:
<QUOTE><P>Although we agree that it is open to an appellate court to find that an inference of fact made by the trial judge is clearly wrong, we would add the caution that where evidence exists to support this inference, an appellate court will be hard pressed to find a palpable and overriding error. As stated above, trial courts are in an advantageous position when it comes to assessing and weighing vast quantities of evidence. In making a factual inference, the trial judge must sift through the relevant facts, decide on their weight, and draw a factual conclusion. Thus, where evidence exists which supports this conclusion, interference with this conclusion entails interference with the weight assigned by the trial judge to the pieces of evidence (&para;22).</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>54. Put another way, as long as there was some evidence upon which the trial judge could have reached his conclusions, that is sufficient.</P>
<P>55. There are two distinct bases upon which an appellate court can set aside a trial judge's findings of fact which, with respect, the appellant has conflated in its argument. The two considerations are:
<P1>(a) whether the trial judge erred by failing to consider relevant evidence; and,</P1>
<P1>(b) whether the trial judge's reasons for judgment were insufficient.</P1></P>
<P>56. The appellants argue that, in reaching its factual findings, the trial judge failed to consider the evidence of Royce and Mrs. Wright, which failure is allegedly evidenced: a) the unresolved contradictions their evidence presented, and b) the lack of reference to their evidence in the reasons for judgment. With respect, neither of these reasons are sufficient to have an appellant court interfere with a trial judge's findings.</P>
<P>57. Contrary to the position taken by the appellants' in their factum, their argument that the trial judge ignored, forgot, or misconceived relevant evidence is not based on an error of law, but rather, challenges the trial judge's findings of fact.
<P1>BOA Tab 1, <CASEREF><SOC>Bystedt (Guardian ad litem of) v. Hay</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 124</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>58. What the appellants really urge in their factum is to have this honourable court find that the trial judge erred because he did not prefer the evidence they advanced over the evidence of the plaintiff.</P>
<P>59. Contrary to the requirements of <EM>Housen</EM>, they do not allege that there exists no evidence upon which the trial judge could have based his findings. Rather, the appellants argue the evidence preferred by the trial judge was contradicted by witnesses called by the defendants and urges this Court to conclude that the failure to refer to the evidence of Mrs. Wright and Royce and to explain the contradictions in their evidence means the trial judge failed to consider their evidence.</P>
<P>60. It is not necessary for a trial judge to resolve conflicts in the evidence if he or she is able to draw a conclusion based on all of the evidence.
<P1>BOA Tab 10, <CASEREF><SOC>Slocan Forest Products Ltd. v. Trapper Enterprises Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 BCCA 351</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>61. Where the appellants allege the failure of the trial judge to consider relevant evidence, the appellants bear the onus of demonstrating a failure to consider such evidence. The mere absence of any reference to evidence in reasons for judgment does not establish that the trial judge failed to consider that evidence. The appellant must point to something in the trial record, usually in the reasons, which justifies the conclusion that the trial judge failed to consider certain evidence.
<P1>BOA Tab 11, <CASEREF><SOC>Waxman v. Waxman</SOC><YEAR>2004</YEAR><CITE>186 O.A.C. 201</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> &para;343</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Application:</UNDER></TI>
<P>62. It is clear from the transcripts and exhibits that there was sufficient evidence for the trial judge to have made the findings that he did.</P>
<P>63. Whether or not Wright mentioned to Royce that he wanted to have Long named as his nominee for the purpose of the Royalty Agreement is irrelevant, as there was no discussion of how and why Long was being named as the &ldquo;nominee&rdquo;, nor was the agreement that was said to paper the transaction ever shown to Royce in order to obtain his opinion with respect to its sufficiency given any stated intent. While counsel would have this court conclude that the &ldquo;paperwork&rdquo; being referred to was the Blank Agreement, this is a speculative conclusion that the appellants are asking this court to draw.</P>
<P>64. On this very issue, Royce's evidence was as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Q And then my question is, when did you find out from Mr. Wright, if you remember, that Mr. Long was going to have some kind of involvement with respect to the royalty?</P>
<P>A I'm not quite sure of the time, but it was mentioned to me that Gerry wanted to have the royalty recorded in the name of Mr. Long.</P>
<P>Q Yes. And what&mdash;did you have a conversation with Mr. Wright about that?</P>
<P>A Absolutely. I said that it's really a bad idea to do. You don't want to put something in someone else's name because it could only cause problems. I have seen enough family businesses where there's money on the table, everyone forgets what was said, too many on purpose. So I said, &ldquo;If you put it in anyone's name other than your own, make sure that you have paperwork that satisfies you that you retain the interest in that royalty.&rdquo;</P>
<P>Q Can you explain a little bit, though, that Mr. Wright said he wanted to put the royalty, or record the royalty in Mr. Long's name? So what&mdash;did you have any understanding as to whether or not Mr. Long had an interest then, a beneficial interest in the royalty?</P>
<P>A My understanding was that&mdash;only this is what I counseled Gerry&mdash;that if you retain the royalty&mdash;you know, you retain the beneficial interest, make sure that if it's in&mdash;if someone else's name appears, that you cover that off such that anyone looking at it would say, well, it might be in person x's name&mdash;may Long's name&mdash;but I' the one that has beneficial interest. And that was for him to do.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>TEB Tab 32, pp. 869-870, ll. 35&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;21</P1>
<QUOTE><P>Q Mr. Royce, earlier in the day, before the lunch break, you were explaining to us that you had told Mr. Wright on a few occasions that he should make sure paper&mdash;paper the transfer of the royalty. I think you are speaking particularly of Mr. Long.</P>
<P>A Yes.</P>
<P>Q So what did you mean by that exactly when you say &ldquo;make sure you have it papered&rdquo;?</P>
<P>A Well, obviously the entitlement and beneficial interest which would be shareholders of Crew Capital, Gerry Wright was one.</P>
<P>Q Yes?</P>
<P>A
<P1>John Darch and Bob Anderson. So they would be getting the, you know, beneficial interest, all other things being equal.</P1>
<P1>So when Gerry mentioned that he wanted to have David Long as his nominee, I said: Well, just make sure that it is papered properly so that if the intent is that you keep the beneficial interest, then there is some paperwork to support that, notwithstanding the fact that somebody else' name is on it.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>Q Now, do you know if any paperwork along those lines was ever drawn up?</P>
<P>A I have no knowledge of it being drawn up, but I stressed it to Gerry several times, and by the end he was saying, &ldquo;Yes, it's taken care of.&rdquo;</P>
<P>Q Did he say anything else with respect to the paperwork?</P>
<P>A Yes, he said that he has paperwork in his safe. So I said, fine, and left it at that.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>TEB Tab 36, pp. 877 to 878, ll. 35&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;19</P1></P>
<P>65. The only time that Royce gave clear evidence that he understood that Long was going to be holding the Royalty as nominee was after a leading question in reexamination.
<P1>TEB Tab 41, pp. 900 to 901, ll. 9&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;3</P1></P>
<P>66. At no time did Royce give unprompted evidence that Wright told him that he was, in fact, retaining 100% of the beneficial interest in the Royalty that had been placed in Long's name. Even if Wright had told Royce this, what is clear from the trial judge's reasons, which are supportable by the evidence at trial, is that he concluded that Wright was capable of putting forward self-serving stories when it suited his needs.
<P1>RAB pgs. 3&ndash;6, Oral Ruling, paras. 5 and 6</P1></P>
<P>67. The only understanding Royce gathered in relation to the nature of Long and Wright's respective interests in the Royalty were provided by Wright. At no time did Royce see any objective evidence related to same.</P>
<P>68. With respect to the evidence of Mrs. Wright, there is no question that the plaintiff did not accept any of her evidence at trial. She was vigorously cross examined and her evidence was heavily tested by the plaintiff. In the end, by virtue of his reasons, it is clear that the trial judge concluded that her evidence was not accepted. This was a reasonable conclusion that the trial judge was entitled to reach based upon the evidence presented at trial. No explanation is required by the trial judge in reaching this conclusion. In addition, it cannot be ignored that Mrs. Wright has a vested interest in the outcome of this action and that her interests are fully aligned with those of the appellants.</P>
<P>69. With respect to the trust issue, it is clear that the trial judge concluded that it was the intention of Wright to gift half of the beneficial interest in the Royalty to Long at the time the Royalty Agreement was entered into. As a result, the trial judge was not obliged to deal with the presumption of resulting trust.</P>
<P>70. While it is the position of the appellants that all three reasons given by the trial judge were contradicted by the evidence, this would only be the case if the plaintiff's evidence had not been believed. Long was providing a service to Wright in holding his half of the beneficial interest in trust which was not dissimilar to many of the &ldquo;services&rdquo; that he had provided to Wright in the past. Of note, Wright shared litigation proceeds with Long on a 50/50 basis for a defamation case he had brought and funded in both their names. With respect to the sheltering of half of the Royalty interest from Mrs. Wright, in the reasoning set out in their factum, the appellants have failed to consider the Canadian tax consequences if the Royalty was held and taxed in Canada. A reasonable and plausible explanation was given for the creation of the Blank Transfer Agreement which was contrary to Wright's assertion that it was to document his 100% beneficial interest in the Royalty.
<P1>TEB Tab 24, pp. 709 to 710, ll. 45&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;12</P1></P>
<P>71. Of note, all of the arguments put forward by the appellants in their factum were made in their written closing submissions and rejected by the trial judge.
<P1>RAB pgs. 54&ndash;70, Outline of Submissions of the Defendants</P1></P>
<P>72. There is nothing in the reasons for judgment which could demonstrate that the trial judge ignored, forgot or misconceived relevant evidence and, as a result, a palpable and overriding error cannot be found. With respect to this aspect of the appeal, the appellants have failed to raise an issue which calls for appellate intervention and this portion of the appeal ought to be dismissed.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Alleged Insufficient Reasons for Judgment</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Law:</UNDER></TI>
<P>73. The appellants allege that the trial judge failed to provide sufficient reasons for judgment because he failed:
<P1>(a) to refer to the evidence of Royce;</P1>
<P1>(b) to attempt to reconcile the evidence of Royce with [the trial judge's] finding that Wright intended to gift the plaintiff 50% of the Royalty;</P1>
<P1>(c) to refer to the evidence of Mrs. Wright; and,</P1>
<P1>(d) to explain contradictions between Mrs. Wright's evidence and the trial judge's findings of fact.</P1></P>
<P>74. In his reasons for judgment, the trial judge identified the issue at trial to be that of conflicting credibility.</P>
<P>75. The primary issue to be determined was: when the Royalty interest was transferred to Long, did Wright retain 100% of the beneficial interest, or was 50% of the beneficial interest gifted to Long. The trial judge resolved this issue in favour of Long, concluding: &ldquo;On the evidence, I think Mr. Long's version of events is more probable.&rdquo;</P>
<P>76. The preference of one witness's version of events may well result in an implicit rejection of evidence to the contrary:
<QUOTE><P>However, in civil cases in which there is conflicting testimony, the judge is deciding whether a fact occurred on a balance of probabilities. In such cases, provided the judge has not ignored evidence, finding the evidence of one party credible may well be conclusive of the result because that evidence is inconsistent with that of the other party. In such cases, believing one party will mean explicitly or implicitly that the other party was not believed on the important issue in the case. That may be especially true where a plaintiff makes allegations that are altogether denied by the defendant as in this case.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>BOA Tab 2, <CASEREF><SOC>F.H. v. McDougall</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>86</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>77. There is no need, much less requirement, that a trial judge analyze the evidence of a witness who he has disbelieved on the major point in the trial:
<QUOTE><P>I do not suggest trial judges are required to mention every factual issue which arises on the evidence. Usually, when a trial judge does not mention an important matter it is permissible to assume that it was considered and weighed.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>BOA Tab 4, <CASEREF><SOC>Garda v. Osborne</SOC><CITE>[1996] B.C.J. No. 442</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>72 B.C.A.C. 101</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> &para;43 (citations omitted)</P1></P>
<P>78. The foregoing presumption&mdash;that a trial judge has considered the evidence in its entirety&mdash;was reiterated by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Housen</EM>. In <EM>Housen</EM> the court stated that:
<QUOTE><P>This presumption, absent sufficient evidence of misapprehension or neglect, is consistent with the high level of error required by the test of &ldquo;palpable and overriding&rdquo; error. We reiterate that it is open to the trial judge to prefer the testimony of certain witnesses over others and to place more weight on some parts of the evidence than others, particularly where there is conflicting evidence. The mere fact that the trial judge did not discuss a certain point or certain evidence in depth is not sufficient grounds for appellate interference.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>BOA Tab 5, <EM>Housen</EM> &para;72 (citations omitted)</P1></P>
<P>79. In discussing these same principles in <CASEREF><SOC>Shannon v. Shannon</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court added the following:
<QUOTE><P>It is now settled law that there is no free-standing right of appeal on the adequacy or sufficiency of a judge's reasons. Moreover, even where the logical connection between the evidence and the decision cannot be discerned (i.e., the reasons are objectively inadequate), appellate intervention will not be justified if the record itself permits meaningful appellate review. This is evident from the comments of Mr. Justice Bastarache and Madam Justice Abella, for the majority of a five-judge panel in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Gagnon</SOC><CITE>2006 SCC 17</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2006] 1 S.C.R. 621</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>[13] ... Finding an error of law due to insufficient reasons requires two stages of analysis: (1) are the reasons inadequate; (2) if so, do they prevent appellate review? In other words, the Court [in <EM>Sheppard</EM>] concluded that even if the reasons are objectively inadequate, they sometimes do not prevent appellate review because the basis for the verdict is obvious on the face of the record. But if the reasons are both inadequate and inscrutable, a new trial is required.</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE>
<P1>BOA Tab 9, <CASEREF><SOC>Shannon v. Shannon</SOC><CITE>2011 BCCA 397</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Application:</UNDER></TI>
<P>80. In the case at hand, the reasons for judgment of the trial judge are not insufficient and, even if they were, a review of the record clearly demonstrates an evidentiary basis for his conclusions.</P>
<P>81. In his judgment, the trial judge gave his reasons for preferring the evidence of Long over Wright. Specifically, he held as follows:
<P1>(a) The evidence of Darch was in line with the evidence of Long. Darch was a neutral witness having no bias in favour of either of the parties. He had no financial interest in the outcome of the litigation (AR Tab 26, Reasons, paras. 47 to 50);</P1>
<P1>(b) The representation of a beneficial 50:50 share of the Royalty was consistent with the past friendship and financial business relationship of the parties (AR Tab 26, Reasons, para. 57);</P1>
<P1>(c) Despite being warned to &ldquo;properly paper&rdquo; the true nature of the 50:50 interest arrangement in the Royalty interest to Long, Wright chose not to leave a paper trail, ostensibly for personal domestic and tax reasons (AR Tab 26, Reasons, para. 57);</P1>
<P1>(d) Darch corroborated Long's assertion that Wright preferred a half than a quarter interest in the Royalty (AR Tab 26, Reasons, para. 57);</P1>
<P1>(e) Although Wright is a sophisticated and experienced businessman, he chose not to leave a traceable paper trail about the true nature of the transfer, being concerned about potential taxation consequences if the true nature of the transfer was paper. He could, however, have effected a private declaration of trust document between himself and Long, known only between themselves, which he did not (AR Tab 26, Reasons, para. 57).</P1></P>
<P>82. Of note, with respect to paragraph 81(e) above, the appellants assert that the trial judge erred in his conclusions about the evidence of Mrs. Wright, who is not an independent witness, was entirely aligned with Wright's version of events, which version was expressly rejected by the trial judge. There is no obligation on a trial judge to reference each piece of evidence or to include an analysis of each witness called at trial.</P>
<P>83. Further, it is respectfully submitted that the appellants exaggerate the importance of Mrs. Wright's evidence. The appellants state that it is an error for the trial judge to have found Wright was trying to hide the Royalty interest from Mrs. Wright given that she had been given a copy of the Blank Transfer Agreement.</P>
<P>84. However, while stated as a conclusive fact, one could easily conclude, on the evidence at trial, that Mrs. Wright had not been given a copy of the Blank Transfer Agreement. First, the note from the lawyer says &ldquo;corrected agreement&rdquo;. There was no evidence of a corrected Blank Transfer Agreement outside of the oral evidence of Wright and Mrs. Wright. To the contrary, on the objective evidence, a copy of a corrected Royalty Agreement was produced in the litigation immediately behind the note that was purported to have attached a corrected Blank Transfer Agreement. The argument that the note referred to the Blank Transfer Agreement rather than the corrected Royalty Agreement, is not plausible let alone a palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>85. Even if one were to conclude that Mrs. Wright did have access to the Blank Transfer Agreement, it does not mean that she knew the true nature of how the Royalty was being held by Long or Wright's intentions. The uncontroverted evidence was that Wright was having an affair with Ms. Sanksuwan at that time and that he was talking about moving to Thailand. In addition, the clear evidence from Mrs. Wright was that she did not know how the Royalty was paid for and flat out denied that the funds were transferred from Long to Crew.</P>
<P>86. Further, the allegation that the Blank Transfer Agreement was in Wright's safe in West Vancouver cannot be borne out on the evidence either. The Red Branch Transfer Agreement is a nearly word for word reproduction of the Blank Transfer Agreement. Wright testified that the Blank Transfer Agreement was in his safe in West Vancouver when he drafted the Red Branch Transfer Agreement in Thailand. When asked how he reproduced it so closely from Thailand, he initially claimed to have drafted it from memory. When pushed, he then went onto say that he had a copy of the first page but not the rest. He finally attempted to claim that he had a copy but not the original. Put simply, his version of events kept changing when his evidence was shown to be impossible.
<P1>TEB Tab 22, pp. 649 to 652, ll. 45&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;47</P1></P>
<P>87. This testimony is unbelievable. The only possible explanation is that he had the Blank Transfer Agreement in his possession because it had been removed from the safe, which he never claimed, or that it had never been in the safe to begin with.</P>
<P>88. The trial judge expressly rejected Wright's version of events. The testimony of Mrs. Wright was, obviously, an attempt to exactly re-state that version.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>ISSUE 2</UNDER></TI>
<P>89. The appellants argue that the trial judge erred in law and made palpable and overriding errors of fact, by failing to properly assess the credibility of the plaintiff and Wright.</P>
<P>90. The entirety of the appellants' Factum is based on the contention that the trial judge erred in preferring the evidence of the plaintiff over the evidence of the defendants.</P>
<P>91. While the first issue in their Factum represents an attempt by the appellants to get around the high standard of review for a trial judge's findings of fact, the second issue is a straightforward challenge of the trial judge's credibility assessment.</P>
<P>92. Factual findings of a trial judge based on considerations of the evidence are not subject to appellate interference absent a palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>93. As noted above, where there is some evidence to support the factual conclusions of the trial judge, the appellate court will not substitute its view.</P>
<P>94. In the case at hand, the appellants point to the very evidence accepted by the trial judge at paragraph 56 of their Factum.</P>
<P>95. Paragraphs 57 to 63 of the appellants' Factum consist of references to contradicting evidence advanced by the defendant at trial. The contradicting evidence cited by the appellants is insufficient to establish that the trial judge made a palpable and overriding error in his assessment of the credibility of Long and Wright at trial.</P>
<P>96. As set out above, there were many examples of gratuitous funding and gifts by Wright to Long, including the splitting of litigation proceeds for which Wright paid 100% of the legal fees. Further, there was sufficient evidence for the trial judge to find that Wright did not have any intention of paying Canadian taxes on any proceeds generated by the Royalty and, as a result, accepting the half rather than a quarter argument was a reasonable conclusion for the trial judge to come to. Finally, an alternate, plausible explanation was given for the existence of the Blank Transfer Agreement that did not support Wright's assertion that this document was to protect his beneficial interest. Instead, it was the evidence of Long that Wright had him sign this document so that the Royalty could be moved quickly if necessary.</P>
<P>97. It was also made abundantly clear that Wright would say anything at trial in order to provide a self-serving story. Examples of this are as follows:
<P1>(a) Wright insisted that Long had signed the Promissory Note much earlier than February 1999 when all of the objective evidence and the testimony of Darch and Royce established otherwise (TEB Tab 14, pp. 605&ndash;608, ll. 18&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;42; TEB Tab 15, p. 609, ll. 28&ndash;30; TEB Tab 16, p. 610, ll. 5&ndash;8; TEB Tab 10, pp. 560-561, ll. 35&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;36; TEB Tab 11, pp. 579-580, ll. 44&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;10; TEB Tab 21, p. 630, ll. 2&ndash;23);</P1>
<P1>(b) Wright insisted that the Opinion had nothing to do with steps that he took in relation to the Royalty and what he asked of Long (TEB Tab 17, p. 611, ll. 14&ndash;26);</P1>
<P1>(c) Wright insisted that any reference he made to Long in emails to legal counsel was a reference to himself even if he referred to both Long and himself in the same email (TEB Tab 8, p. 552, ll. 17&ndash;42; TEB Tab 9, p. 555, ll. 11&ndash;18; TEB Tab 10, pp. 560-561, ll. 35&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;36; TEB Tab 11, pp. 579-580, ll. 44&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;10; TEB Tab 18, pp. 612-613, ll. 12&ndash;47 &amp; 1; TEB Tab 23, pp. 659-660, ll. 11&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;28);</P1>
<P1>(d) Wright insisted that Long could not have been at the Christening of his daughter since none of his children were Christened and he maintained this position until faced with the certificate of his daughter's Christening (TEB Tab 13, p. 596, ll. 24&ndash;28; TEB Tab 25, pp. 736&ndash;738, ll. 16&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;24); and,</P1>
<P1>(e) Wright insisted that he had never lied to any of his wives about his extramarital affairs, but instead, chose not to talk about what he was doing or avoiding answering questions (TEB Tab 12, pp. 590&ndash;592, ll. 37&ndash;47, 1&ndash;47 &amp; 1&ndash;39).</P1></P>
<P>98. With respect, just because a party can point to portions of the evidence, if believed, would be supportive of its version of events, does not mean that the trial judge must accept that evidence. The trial judge considered all of the evidence tendered at trial and found that the plaintiff's version of events was more plausible than that of the defendants.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>99. That this appeal be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</P>
