<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT <EM>FORM 109 (RULE 22-2(2) AND (7))</EM></TI>
<P>I, Owais Ahmed, Barrister &amp; Solicitor, of 3200 - 650 West Georgia Street, in the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, MAKE OATH AND SAY AS FOLLOWS:</P>
<P>1. I am a lawyer with Harper Grey LLP, solicitors for the Appellants, Red Branch Investments Limited and Gerald Wright herein, and as such I have personal knowledge of the matters and facts herein deposed to save and except where the same are stated to be made upon information and belief and as to the latter I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>2. All of the correspondence exchanged by my office and C. Michelle Tribe, counsel for the respondent (plaintiff) pertaining to this appeal are attached to Affidavit #1 of Gabeba Slamang, sworn September 21, 2016 and filed by the respondent, and I have not therefore attached the same to my affidavit.</P>
<P>3. As set out in my email to Ms. Tribe of April 4, 2016, my intention on that date was to bring an application on behalf of my clients for an extension so that the appellants' materials could be filed and to seek a stay of the execution of the judgment below.</P>
<P>4. It made sense to me for both applications to be heard at the same time, because the test for an extension and a stay of execution both involved the issue of whether the appeal had any merit.</P>
<P>5. Unfortunately, the appellant, Gerald Wright, was out of the country on business in South East Asia (including remote areas of Laos where communication was difficult), and I did not receive an original sworn affidavit from him for use in the application until April 15, 2016. That affidavit was sworn before a consular official in the Canadian Embassy in Bangkok, Thailand.</P>
<P>6. However, I determined that further changes needed to be made to Mr. Wright's affidavit and it had to be sworn again. That did not occur until April 28, 2016, by which time Mr. Wright had returned to Canada and I was able to meet with him. A true copy of Mr. Weight's affidavit is attached hereto as Exhibit <BOLD>&ldquo;A&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>7. I intended to quickly thereafter file the appellants' application materials. Unfortunately around April 30, 2016, my mother's health began to deteriorate. My mother suffers from medullary sponge kidney disease, and her condition began to worsen significantly around the end of April, 20 16. She is now facing kidney failure and her treatment options are limited.</P>
<P>8. Consequently, I was out of the office from April 30 to mid-May 2016.</P>
<P>9. While I am hopeful that my mother's condition will improve, her condition remains poor to date and that has been very distressing for me.</P>
<P>10. Since my return to the office in mid-May 2016, I have done my best to remain in the office and fulfill my work commitments, despite the emotional stress relating to my mother's health. I regret that I was not successful in this case and that the application for an extension was not brought sooner. The delay is entirely attributable to me.</P>
<P>11. From mid-May 2016 to date, I have been extremely busy at work with a number of court appearances and lengthy hearings before various administrative tribunals. I do not advance my busy work load as an excuse for my failure to bring the appellants' application for an extension soon after Mr. Wright's affidavit was sworn on April 28, 2016, but it has made it more difficult to deal with my mother's health condition and to spend time with her.</P>
<P>12. In hindsight, I acknowledge that I should have had someone else take carriage of the file, but at the time I thought it would be too difficult to bring someone else up to speed on the file given that no other lawyer has worked on it with me and because I believed that I would be able to bring the application sooner despite my mother's health.</P>
