<P>1. The respondent/plaintiff seeks an order dismissing the within appeal as abandoned pursuant to section 10(2)(e) and 28 of the <EM>Court of Appeal Act</EM> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Act</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), and an order for its costs of the appeal and this application.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>BACKGROUND FACTS</TI>
<P>2. The plaintiff commenced the underlying action by notice of civil claim on April 16, 2012 claiming that the defendants held one-half of a mineral royalty in trust for the plaintiff, which trust had been breached. The defendants opposed the relief sought by the plaintiff, alleging an alternate version of events in their response to civil claim.</P>
<P>3. Trial of the action was heard over the course of 16 days in 2015. In written reasons for judgment, released November 27, 2015 (<BOLD>&ldquo;Reasons for Judgment&rdquo;</BOLD>), Justice Wong granted judgment in favour of the plaintiff. In preferring the plaintiff's evidence, Justice Wong found that the defendants' held 50% of the royalty interest in trust for the plaintiff, and an order after trial was entered on March 30, 2016 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Trial Order&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>4. On application by the plaintiff, Justice Wong granted the plaintiff special costs of the trial, to be held in a solicitor's trust account pending the outcome of this appeal and an order after application was entered on March 30, 2016 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Special Costs Order&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>5. The defendants filed a notice of appeal on December 24, 2015, and amended notice of appeal on March 10, 2016, appealing the Trial Order and Special Costs Order.</P>
<P>6. On February 11, 2016, counsel for the plaintiff advised that the plaintiff would not agree to extend any procedural time periods in the <EM>Court of Appeal Rules</EM> (the &ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Rules</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>7. On March 16, 2016, the defendants sought the plaintiff's consent to the preparation and filing of a joint appeal book. By letter dated March 21, 2016, plaintiff's counsel advised that the plaintiff did not consent to a joint appeal book.</P>
<P>8. On March 21, 2016, counsel for the defendants' advised by letter that, as a result of a mistaken assumption that the parties would file a joint appeal book, he was not confident that the defendants would be able to file the appeal book the next day. Counsel for the defendants sought an extension of time, which the plaintiff did not agree to.</P>
<P>9. On April 4, 2016, counsel for the defendants sought plaintiffs' counsel's availability for applications to extend time and a stay of execution. On April 4, 2016, counsel for the plaintiff provided her available dates. Since April 4, 2016, there have been no further communications from counsel for the defendants, nor anyone else on behalf of the defendants. To date, the defendants' factum and appeal book are over 180 days late and no application materials have been received by the plaintiff. The mistaken assumption regarding a joint appeal book is not a plausible explanation for the delay in filing the appeal book, and no explanation for the delay in filing the factum has ever been offered.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>ARGUMENT</TI>
<P>10. Sections 10(2)(e) and 28 of the <EM>Act</EM> grant a justice the authority to dismiss an appeal as abandoned for failure to comply with the <EM>Act</EM> or <EM>Rules</EM>: <CASEREF><SOC>George v. McMahon</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 497</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF> (in Chambers) [&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>George #1</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;] <BOLD>[TAB 1],</BOLD> aff'd 2009 BCCA 76 [<BOLD>&ldquo;George #2&rdquo;</BOLD>] <BOLD>[TAB 2].</BOLD></P>
<P>11. In <CASEREF><SOC>Redpath v. Redpath</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 400</CITE></CASEREF> (in Chambers), the Court held that the factors to be considered on an application to dismiss an appeal are the <EM>Davies</EM> factors (at &para;15 <BOLD>[TAB 3]</BOLD>): (i) whether there was a <EM>bona fide</EM> intention to appeal; (ii) when the respondents were informed of the intention; (iii) whether the respondents would be unduly prejudiced by an extension; (iv) whether there is merit in the appeal; and (v) the interests of justice.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Bona Fide</EM> Intention to Appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. The defendants' failure to prosecute their appeal demonstrates that they no longer have a <EM>bona fide</EM> intention to appeal: <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia (Attorney General) v. Malik</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 58</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF> (in Chambers) <BOLD>[TAB 4].</BOLD></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Prejudice</UNDER></TI>
<P>13. Prejudice can be inferred from a delay which deprives the plaintiff of the benefit of the relief sought, and awarded, at trial: <EM>Redpath</EM> &para;17 <BOLD>[TAB 3]</BOLD>; <EM>George #2</EM> &para;14 <BOLD>[TAB 2].</BOLD></P>
<P>14. This Court has found delays of three and six months to be prejudicial: <EM>Redpath</EM> <BOLD>[TAB 3],</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Casoli v. Hearndon</SOC><YEAR>1984</YEAR><CITE>57 B.C.L.R. 10</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A. in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[TAB 5].</BOLD></P>
<P>15. The defendants' factum and appeal book are over 180 days overdue, which delay has deprived the plaintiff of certainty and the relief and costs awarded by Justice Wong.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Merits of Appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. In the case at hand, Justice Wong identified the issue for trial as &ldquo;conflicting credibility between the parties as to their agreed arrangement&rdquo;. After considering all of the evidence, Justice Wong preferred the plaintiff's version of events, and rendered judgment entirely in the plaintiff's favour: Reasons for Judgment &para;5, &para;57&ndash;59.</P>
<P>17. The standard of review on an appeal raising assessments of witness credibility and findings of fact is palpable and overriding error. Due to the high standard of review, the merits of an appeal will generally be considered weak where the issues involve fin dings of fact: <CASEREF><SOC>Manjit International Development Ltd. v. Ng</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 429</CITE><PARANUM>10-11</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[TAB 6];</BOLD> <EM>George #1</EM> &para;28 <BOLD>[TAB 1];</BOLD> <EM>George #2</EM> &para;13 <BOLD>[TAB 2];</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Rainbow Country Estates Ltd. v. Whistler (Resort Municipality)</SOC><CITE>2011 BCCA 38</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF> (in Chambers) <BOLD>[TAB 8].</BOLD></P>
<P>18. A court should set aside a costs award, including an order for special costs, only if the trial judge has made an error in principle or if the costs award is plainly wrong: <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Open Window Bakery Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 9</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[TAB 9].</BOLD></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Interests of Justice</UNDER></TI>
<P>19. A delay shall not be excused on the basis of busy counsel or complex facts: <EM>Redpath</EM> &para;20 <BOLD>[TAB 3]</BOLD>; <EM>George #1</EM> &para;25 <BOLD>[TAB 1].</BOLD></P>
<P>20. The appellant has failed to comply with the <EM>Act</EM> without satisfactory explanation. The plaintiff is entitled to a timely and final resolution to this matter, as well as the relief and costs awarded at trial. The interests of justice fall in favour of dismissing the appeal.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Date: 21/SEPT/2016</P>
