<P>1. The appellants oppose the order sought by the respondent to dismissed the appeal as abandoned, and instead seek an order granting an extension to file their factum, appeal book and transcript extracts pursuant to s. 10(2)(d) of the <EM>Court of Appeal Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 77.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>BACKGROUND</UNDER></TI>
<P>2. The appellants submit that the relevant background facts are as follows:
<P1>a. The appellants filed their Notice of Appeal within the time provided in the <EM>Rules</EM> on December 24, 2016;</P1>
<P1>b. The appellants filed their appeal record and five volumes of transcripts, at considerable cost, within the time provided in the <EM>Rules</EM> on February 22, 2016;</P1>
<P1>c. On March 16, 2016, counsel for the appellants advised counsel for the respondent that they the appellants would not be referring to a significant number of the exhibits from the trial in their factum, and inquired whether the plaintiff would agree to the parties filing a Joint Appeal Book;</P1>
<P1>d. In the afternoon on March 21, 2016, having not heard back from counsel for the respondent, counsel for the appellants followed up on the inquiry by voice message and email.</P1>
<P1>e. Counsel for the respondent responded by email on March 21, 2016 and advised that it she did not agree to the filing of a Joint Appeal Book</P1>
<P1>f. On March 22, 2016, counsel for the appellant wrote to counsel for the respondent, seeking consent to an extension of two business days.</P1>
<P1>g. The following day, counsel for the respondent advised that the respondent would not consent to any extension.</P1>
<P1>h. On April 4, 2016, counsel for the appellants wrote to advise that he had instructions to bring an application for an extension to file the outstanding appeal materials and to seek a stay of execution of the judgment below. Counsel further advised that the appellant, Gerald Wright, was in Thailand, but attempts were being made to have his affidavit for the application sworn before a consular official in Bangkok.</P1>
<P1>i. As set out in the undersigned's affidavit, Mr. Wright's affidavit was not sworn until April 28, 2016, after he had returned to Canada.</P1>
<P1>j. As detailed in the undersigned's affidavit, in late April, 2016 his mother's health began to deteriorate and he was out of the office in early May, 2016. The undersigned's mother's poor health persists, and it has contributed to the delay.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>ARGUMENT</TI>
<P>3. The factors to be considered on an application to extent the time to taken any steps necessary in the prosecution of an appeal, were set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Davies v. C.I.B.C.</SOC><YEAR>1987</YEAR><CITE>15 B.C.L.R. (2d) 256</CITE><PAGENUM>at 259-260</PAGENUM><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, and are as follows:
<P1>a. Was there a <EM>bona fide</EM> intention to appeal?</P1>
<P1>b. When were the respondents informed of the intention?</P1>
<P1>c. Would the respondents be unduly prejudiced by an extension of time?</P1>
<P1>d. Is there merit in the appeal?</P1>
<P1>e. Is it in the interests of justice that an extension be granted?</P1></P>
<P>4. The fifth question &ldquo;encompasses the other four questions and states the decisive question&rdquo; and &ldquo;the interests of justice factor is not to be applied independently of the other factors: <CASEREF><SOC>Salfinger v. Salfinger</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 217</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Perren v. Lalari</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 564</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>5. The test for an extension of time to take a step in the prosecution of an appeal is less stringent than the application of the test in the context of an extension of time to appeal or to seek leave to appeal: <CASEREF><SOC>Besic v. Kerenyi</SOC><CITE>2011 BCCA 503</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The appellants have had a <EM>bone fide</EM> intention to appeal throughout, and the respondents were informed of the intention</TI>
<P>6. The appellants clearly have held a <EM>bona fide</EM> intention to appeal, as evidenced by the timely filing of their Notice of Appeal, Appeal Record, and five volumes of transcripts from the 16 day trial at considerable cost. The respondents have been informed of the intention to appeal by way of the same.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The respondent would not be <UNDER>unduly</UNDER> prejudiced by an extension of time</TI>
<P>7. There is no evidence that the respondent has suffered any prejudice as a result of the delay or will be <UNDER>unduly</UNDER> prejudiced by an extension of time. The respondent was successful at trial, and a declaration was made by the trial that Red Branch Investments Limited (&ldquo;Red Branch&rdquo;) holds 50% of the royalty at issue in the trial on an express, resulting, and constructive trust on his behalf. The delay in the appeal has not frustrated the respondent's trust interest.</P>
<P>8. Moreover, the royalty is not generating and has never generated any returns.</P>
<P>9. Circumstances in which there is no prejudice, and the delay is explained, weigh in favor of granting the appellant's request for an extension. The Court may still disapprove of and discourage the delay by ordering costs to the respondent on this application: <CASEREF><SOC>George v. McMahon</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 497</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The appeal is meritorious</TI>
<P>10. The grounds of the appeal are, <EM>inter alia</EM> as follows:
<P1>a. The trial judge erred in law by ignoring, forgetting, or misconceiving relevant evidence that went to the core of the case, most notably:
<P2>i. The entire evidence of Paul Royce, a neutral witness who was Mr. Wright's accountant at all relevant times. Mr. Royce testified that Mr. Wright told him that David Long held the royalty solely as a nominee. Mr. Royce was an important witness for the defence, but his evidence is not even referred to in the trial judge's decision.</P2>
<P2>ii. The entire evidence of Gail Wright, Mr. Wright's wife. The trial judge found that a 50% interest in the royalty was given to the respondent by the appellant, in part because the appellant wanted to shelter the royalty from his wife. However, Ms. Wright testified that she was always familiar with the existence of the royalty and knew from the beginning that the respondent held the royalty solely as a nominee. Ms. Wright was an important witness for the defence, yet her evidence was not addressed in the trial judge's decision.</P2>
<P2>iii. The trial judge also did not deal with a contemporaneous note from a lawyer to Gail Wright, enclosing a copy of a document that reflected that the royalty had been transferred to Mr. Long. That evidence directly contradicts the respondent's position and the trial judge's finding, that the transfer of the royalty to the respondent was done in part to shelter it from Ms. Wright.</P2></P1>
<P1>b. The trail judge erred in law by failing to properly assess the credibility of the plaintiff and defendants, or in the alternative, explain the rationale for his credibility findings.</P1></P>
<P>11. The threshold on this part of the test is low, and the appellant need only show that the appeal is not bound to fail: <EM>Salfinger</EM> at para. 17. The appellant has more than met that threshold.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The interests of justice</TI>
<P>12. It is submitted that the following are the relevant factors to the court's consideration of the interests of justice, in addition to what is set out above:
<P1>a. The fact the delay was caused by counsel and an explanation has been advanced, militates in favour of the extension being granted: <CASEREF><SOC>Rowan v. Dunwoody &amp; Company</SOC><CITE>1999 BCCA 755</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF>. This is not one of those &ldquo;rare&rdquo; cases in which the failure of counsel should be visited on the client.</P1>
<P1>b. The delay in question from March 23, 2016 to date is less than one year, and is not inordinate: <CASEREF><SOC>Medar v. Ionescu</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 428</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>c. This case is distinguishable from those in which the lawyer has simply said &ldquo;I was too busy to get the factum done&rdquo;: <CASEREF><SOC>Vaugeois v. Budget Rent-A-Car of B.C. Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 304</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>d. The fact that the appellants have already incurred the cost of transcripts and the appeal record, is an important but not necessarily conclusive factor in favour of allowing an extension of time: <EM>Rowan</EM>, para. 21.</P1>
<P1>e. The finding of breach of trust made against the individual appellant is serious, and his appeal ought to be heard.</P1></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Date: October 19, 2016</P>
<P>&ellip35; Owais Ahmed, Counsel for the Appellants, Gerald Wright and Red Branch Investments</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
