<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, David P. Long, of [location omitted] SWEAR THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am the Respondent/Plaintiff in this appeal and have personal knowledge of the facts and matters herein deposed to save and except where the same are stated to be based on information and belief and where so stated I verily believe the same to be true.</P>
<P>2. Mr. Justice Wong awarded me special costs in the within action on February 9, 2016. As I understand it, on September 18, 2017, my counsel disclosed the litigation file in this matter for the purpose of the assessment of my special costs (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Litigation File&rdquo;</BOLD>). The Litigation File was only disclosed for the limited purpose of assessing my special costs.</P>
<P>3. I have reviewed the Memorandum of Argument filed by the Appellants on November 1, 2017 and Affidavit #1 of Tiffany Hambrook, sworn November 1, 2017, and it appears that the Appellants are alleging that, based upon their review of the Litigation File, I was not truthful in my testimony at trial when I stated that Mr. John Darch had not provided me with any financial assistance in this litigation and that I had never spoke to Mr. John Darch about the within litigation and that I intentionally misled the trial judge on a material issue.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Payment of Legal Fees</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. With respect to the allegation that Mr. Darch provided me with financial assistance in the litigation, this is simply not the case.</P>
<P>5. As I testified at trial, I was providing consulting services for Mr. Darch and some of his companies, through Western Investments Ltd. (<BOLD>&ldquo;Western Investments&rdquo;</BOLD>), from 2011 until April 2014. At the time that this agreement was entered into, I did not have a bank account anywhere in the world, including Canada. As a result, as a term of my engagement, it was requested by me and agreed to by Mr. Darch, that Western Investments would cause funds that were owing to me to be forwarded to various accounts and entities at my direction in lieu of a regular paycheck provided that I agreed to pay any and all bank charges related to these requests out of my earned salary.</P>
<P>6. I was paid a consulting fee for managing various potential projects in Thailand that varied between $10,000 and $15,000 per month plus a foreign living allowance of $2,700 per month. The project had funding problems and payments were spasmodic and, as a result, I would have to wait until funding was received before I could be compensated for my work and request any payments be made.</P>
<P>7. During the course of my consulting work, at my direction, Western Investments forwarded funds to various parties including my wife and children, and Clark Wilson LLP. Other commitments included Glentoran Academy, a soccer program assisting disadvantaged and disabled children near my home in Belfast and the repayment of a personal loan. At all times any funds that were paid out were funds owing to me for work performed. At no time did I receive an advance in order to make any of these payments. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my Affidavit is a true copy of a sample of a payment request I sent to Mr. Darch with the relevant account information removed.</P>
<P>8. As agreed, I paid all service and banking fees for all of these transfers and payments out of my earnings.</P>
<P>9. Between March 2012 and December 2013, I earned $307,439.28 for my consulting services in Thailand. Of this amount, between January 13, 2012 and March 17, 2015, I directed $78,420 to be paid to Clark Wilson LLP for my legal accounts.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Communications with Mr. Darch</UNDER></TI>
<P>10. In their argument and supporting affidavit, the Appellants point to a handful of email communications between Mr. Darch, me and my lawyers. In particular, they have pointed to the following emails:
<P1>(a) A June 17, 2012 email from Mr. Darch to me (the <BOLD>&ldquo;June 17 2012 Email&rdquo;</BOLD>) in which Mr. Darch provides extensive evidence and some advice with respect to the conduct of the litigation;</P1>
<P1>(b) A June 18, 2012 email from me to my lawyer, Mr. Barry Fraser, with a copy to both Ms. Michelle Tribe, one of my other lawyers, and Mr. Darch in which I advise that Mr. Darch had documents for my lawyers and requesting that my lawyers meet with Mr. Darch, who I described as &ldquo;a very advantageous, if somewhat reluctant, witness should we go to court.&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(c) A June 28, 2012 email from Mr. Darch to Ms. Tribe and me in which he advised on a meeting he had with Alice, another one third holder of the royalty, and David Anderson, her brother-in-law and lawyer;</P1>
<P1>(d) Two June 28, 2012 emails from Mr. Darch to Ms. Tribe and me in which he advised about communications with Fasken Martineau;</P1>
<P1>(e) A June 30, 2012 email from Mr. Darch to Ms. Tribe and me in which Mr. Darch advised on his attendance at the offices of Fasken Martineau;</P1>
<P1>(f) A December 11, 2012 email from me to Ms. Sekunova in which I ask if we have the documents listed under the Appellants' list of documents as I would like for Mr. Darch to look through them;</P1>
<P1>(g) A December 20, 2012 email from me to Dianne Bishop, then assistant to Ms. Sekunova and Ms. Tribe, copied to Mr. Darch, in which I asked about document production;</P1>
<P1>(h) A December 21, 2012 email from Ms. Bishop to Mr. Darch and copied to me, attaching requested documents;</P1>
<P1>(i) A December 21, 2012 email from Mr. Darch to me and copied to my lawyers, in which Mr. Darch asked about a document found in the Appellants' list of documents;</P1>
<P1>(j) A February 19, 2013 email from me to Ms. Anna Sekunova, one of my lawyers at the time, in which I forwarded the June 17 2012 Email to Ms. Sekunova for her consideration;</P1>
<P1>(k) A February 19, 2013 email from me to Ms. Sekunova in which I forwarded a February 19, 2013 email from Mr. Darch;</P1>
<P1>(l) A February 19, 2013 email from me to Ms. Sekunova to which Mr. Darch was copied;</P1>
<P1>(m) A February 19, 2013 email from Mr. Darch to Ms. Sekunova and me in which Mr. Darch responded to questions from Ms. Sekunova;</P1>
<P1>(n) A February 24, 2013 email from Mr. Darch to Ms. Sekunova and me in which he attached information related to the value of the royalty; and,</P1>
<P1>(o) A March 9, 2015 email from me to Ms. Tribe and Mr. Fraser in which I referenced leaving files in Mr. Darch's office immediately after my examination for discovery in February 2013.</P1></P>
<P>11. The above communications were made during a time when I was in contact with Mr. Darch multiple times per day in relation to the projects that I was providing consulting services on. They were also made over two years before the trial of this action.</P>
<P>12. With respect to any emails sent by or copied to me by Mr. Darch, none of these communications stood out to me at the time that they were sent. In fact, to the best of my recollection, I would quickly scan these emails to determine whether or not they were work related and, if they were not, I would generally take no further action in relation to them other than to forward them to my lawyers in case they contained relevant information.</P>
<P>13. With respect to the June 17 2012 Email, I do not recall reading the entirety of this email at any time. In fact, it was not until I was reviewing my emails communications in February 2013 while preparing for my examinations for discovery that I realized that this email might be of some importance in the litigation. As a result, upon discovering it, I forwarded it Ms. Sekunova for her consideration. Following my forwarding of the June 17 2012 Email, I thought nothing further of it.</P>
<P>14. With respect to the balance of the email communications referred to above, it was my habit to copy Mr. Darch on emails as a means of keeping him advised about matters that pertained to him, such as when he agreed to provide copies of documents to my lawyers that he had in his possession. I also kept Mr. Darch advised about various communications related to document production as I wanted him to have the opportunity to review documents given that he was going to be a witness at trial.</P>
<P>15. Shortly before the trial of this matter was set to commence at the end of March 2015, I did attempt, unsuccessfully, to contact Mr. Darch to confirm that he would still be testifying as a witness as we had not been in communication since April 2014.</P>
<P>16. When preparing for trial in March 2015, I did not turn my mind to nor review any of my previous communications with my counsel or Mr. Darch and, instead, focused on the documents that were to be relied upon at trial. By March 2015 I had forgotten completely about my email communications with Mr. Darch related to anything to do with this litigation, including the June 17 2012 Email.</P>
<P>17. When I gave my evidence at trial, I gave my evidence to the best of my recollection. Specifically:
<P1>(a) When I was asked whether or not Mr. Darch had provided me with assistance in the litigation, I did not consider that he had. While he had met with my lawyers and told me that he was going to provide them with copies of documents that he had in his possession, I did not consider this to be providing me with &ldquo;assistance&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) At no time did Mr. Darch provide me with &ldquo;financial&rdquo; assistance with this litigation;</P1>
<P1>(c) To the best of my recollection, at no time did I meet with Mr. Darch to specifically discuss the issues in this litigation nor did I have litigation specific discussions with him with the exception of a few emails, most of which I did not read. At the time of trial, the only communications that I recalled having with Mr. Darch were to direct him to pay monies owing to me to Clark Wilson for my legal fees and to ensure that confirm that he would be meeting with my lawyers to give them his evidence; and,</P1>
<P1>(d) At the time of trial, I was not certain whether or not Mr. Darch had, in fact, provided copies of documents to my lawyers or where documents that had been produced had originated from, however, I was certain that Mr. Darch had not provided any litigation related documents directly to me.</P1></P>
