<FREEFORM>
<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, C. Michelle Tribe, lawyer, of 1100 - 570 Granville Street, in the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, SWEAR (OR AFFIRM) THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am a partner with Fraser Litigation Group, solicitors for the Respondent/Plaintiff in this appeal and I have personal knowledge of the facts and matters herein deposed to save and except where the same are stated to be based on information and belief and where so stated I verily believe the same to be true.</P>
<P>2. In January 2012, Mr. Barry Fraser was a partner and I was an associate with the law firm Clark Wilson LLP (<BOLD>&ldquo;Clark Wilson&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>3. Also in January 2012, Mr. Long consulted with Mr. Fraser and retained Clark Wilson to assist him in his dispute with Red Branch Investments Limited (<BOLD>&ldquo;Red Branch&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Gerald Wright. Upon Clark Wilson's retainer, I assumed conduct of Mr. Long's file under the direction of Mr. Fraser.</P>
<P>4. The Notice of Civil Claim was filed on April 16, 2012 and served on Mr. Wright in his personal capacity on April 23, 2012. Mr. Wright filed his Response to Civil Claim on May 15, 2012.</P>
<P>5. Because Red Branch is a Hong Kong corporation and because the claim did not fall within section 10 of the <EM>Court Jurisdiction and Proceedings Transfer Act</EM>, RSBC 2003, c 28, on August 14, 2012, we filed and served application materials in order to obtain leave to serve <EM>ex juris</EM> the Notice of Civil Claim on Red Branch, which application was ultimately settled by consent. Red Branch and Mr. Wright filed an Amended Response to Civil Claim on September 18, 2012.</P>
<P>6. In the spring of 2012, I became pregnant with my second child, who was due in early December 2012. In late September 2012, due to medical issues, I was forced to take early leave and, in my absence, Ms. Anna Sekunova, a then associate with Clark Wilson, assumed conduct of Mr. Long's file. On September 12, 2012, prior to being placed on disability leave, I prepared and delivered the plaintiff's first list of documents in this matter.</P>
<P>7. The first list of documents of the defendants was not delivered until December 10, 2012. This list of documents did not include any relevant communications related to the royalty with the exception of the June 7, 2010 email from Mr. Wright to Mr. Gabrielson advising that Mr. Long was transferring the royalty to Red Branch.</P>
<P>8. Mr. Wright did not produce any of the other email communications related to the material facts raised in the litigation until May 23, 2013, after his examination for discovery.</P>
<P>9. Prior to my taking leave, I had been in contact with the law office of Fasken Martineau LLP to review their files related to the royalty at issue in this litigation and, more particularly, for which Mr. Long and Mr. John Darch had been their clients. I did not have a chance to review their records before my unplanned leave.</P>
<P>10. On October 26, 2012, Andrew Gabrielson of Fasken Martineau contacted Mr. Long and Mr. Fraser, with a copy to myself, to advise that their file was available for review. Because Ms. Sekunova was new to the file and we were looking for specific documents, despite being on disability leave, I arranged to attend at the offices of Fasken Martineau on November 1, 2012. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my Affidavit is a true copy of this email exchange.</P>
<P>11. I did in fact attend at the office of Fasken Martineau on November 1, 2012 and reviewed their file materials. Based upon my review, I requested that copies of several documents be made and provided to Clark Wilson for the purpose of this litigation. All of the Fasken Martineau documents produced and relied upon by the plaintiff in this litigation were obtained as a result of my attendance at their office on this date and none of these documents were provided to us by Mr. Darch.</P>
<P>12. Because I was on disability leave, I neither recorded my time nor was the client charged for my attendance at Fasken Martineau's office to review their file.</P>
<P>13. My daughter was born on [date omitted], at which time I started my six month maternity leave.</P>
<P>14. Based upon my review of the file, in my absence, Ms. Sekunova:
<P1>(a) Filed and served a notice of trial for a five day trial set to commence on July 8, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(b) Prepared and served Mr. Long's amended lists of documents dated February 19, 2013 and April 8, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(c) Received the lists of documents prepared by Red Branch and Mr. Wright;</P1>
<P1>(d) Conducted and attended at examinations for discovery on February 20 and 21, 2013; and,</P1>
<P1>(e) Met with Mr. Darch to prepare him as a witness for trial.</P1></P>
<P>15. I returned from my maternity leave on June 3, 2013 and, within days of my return, Ms. Sekunova took an extended sabbatical. As a result, I reassumed conduct of Mr. Long's litigation file.</P>
<P>16. Upon my return to the office, it became clear that it would be impossible for me to prepare this for trial and that insufficient time had been scheduled for same. At the time, it was my view that five days was going to be wholly insufficient for the trial. In addition, I discovered that one of the plaintiff's witnesses, Mr. Mark Andrews, Q.C, was on sabbatical for the year and, as a result, not available to testify. As a result, I sought an adjournment of the July 2013 trial date.</P>
<P>17. The defendants did not consent to such an adjournment and, as a result, a trial management conference was held on June 13, 2013. On June 12, 2013, we filed and served the plaintiff's trial brief, which clearly set out that we intended to call Mr. Darch as a witness and had him scheduled to testify for half a day. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my Affidavit is a true copy of this trial brief.</P>
<P>18. On June 13, 2013, Master Baker ordered the July 2013 trial of the matter adjourned generally.</P>
<P>19. On September 24, 2013, a notice of trial was filed setting the trial of this matter down for March 30, 2015.</P>
<P>20. Very little happened on this file for the balance of 2013 and all of 2014.</P>
<P>21. In March 2014, Mr. Fraser, myself and two other lawyers left Clark Wilson in order to form our own firm. While Mr. Long chose to remain our client, due to a solicitors lien on his file, his file materials from Clark Wilson were retained by them and not released to us at the time of our departure. As a result, I had none of Mr. Long's file materials, including any correspondence, at our new firm.</P>
<P>22. Prior to the trial of this matter, and without the benefit of the file materials being held at Clark Wilson, I caused to be filed a subsequent trial brief in this matter on March 9, 2015, which brief once again disclosed that Mr. Darch would be a witness for the plaintiff. At the T rial Management Conference heard the next day, I was ordered to provide a summary of the evidence of Mr. Darch, which I did that same day. In the summary I provided Mr. Darch's email address so that the defendants could contact him should they wish. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibits &ldquo;C&rdquo; and &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my Affidavit are true copies of this trial brief and the witness summary I provided to Mr. Owais Ahmed, counsel for the defendants.</P>
<P>23. Mr. Long was not able to clear up the solicitor's lien that Clark Wilson had over his file materials until mid-March 2015 and, as a result, I had to conduct almost all of my trial preparation without the benefit of the file materials that were being held by Clark Wilson. With tri al set to commence on March 30, 2015, I received two boxes of files as well as a USB stick containing the electronic files for Mr. Long's matter on March 19, 2015 and a further box containing further documents on March 23, 2015. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibits &ldquo;E&rdquo; and &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> are true copies of the letters enclosing these materials.</P>
<P>24. Of note, I was involved in a five day continuation of a summary trial from March 23 to 27, 2015 and, as a result, I had to have the vast majority of my trial preparation complete by March 22, 2017.</P>
<P>25. Given when Mr. Long's file materials were received and my time constraints, there was no means for me to review the entirety of Mr. Long's file while preparing for trial and, more specifically, past correspondence that had taken place between Mr. Long, Mr. Darch and Ms. Sekunova.</P>
<P>26. In preparing for the upcoming trial, I contacted Mr. Darch in early March 2015 who advised me by both email and by way of telephone conversation that he required a subpoena in order to attend at trial, which I prepared and had delivered to him. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibits &ldquo;G&rdquo; and &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD> are true copies of my emails exchange with Mr. Darch, Mr. Long and myself between and March 4 and 9, 2015 and the subpoena which was delivered to Mr. Darch.</P>
<P>27. On November 27, 2105, the trial judge, Mr. Justice Wong, rendered his judgment, finding in favour of the plaintiff and invited counsel to speak to the matter of costs. On February 9, 2016, Mr. Justice Wong heard the plaintiff's application for special costs and granted them on the basis that Mr. Wright's conduct, both pre-litigation and during the trial, was deserving of rebuke. The defendants appealed the trial decision and, as a result, no steps were taken to have special costs assessed until the appeal process had been resolved.</P>
<P>28. The appeal was heard on May 24, 2017 and, on July 12, 2017, the Court dismissed the defendants' appeal. Following this dismissal, I started to take steps to have the special costs assessed. As part of the special costs assessment, the defendants demanded disclosure of the entirety of the plaintiff's file for which he was seeking special costs. Pursuant to the direction set by the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Gichuru v Smith</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA</CITE></CASEREF>, I caused the entirety of the plaintiff's file to be disclosed to the defendants for which we were seeking special costs. This disclosure was only made for the purpose of assessing special costs and in no way was intended to be a general waiver of privilege over my file.</P>
