<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, John Darch, businessman of [location omitted] SWEAR THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am an entrepreneur and businessman, and as such have knowledge of the matters hereinafter deposed to save and except where stated to be on information and belief and where so stated I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>2. I have been provided with a copy of the application and affidavit in support filed on November 1, 2017, in this matter.</P>
<P>3. I have reviewed those documents and understand from them that it is alleged that I perjured myself and gave false and fraudulent evidence as a witness at the trial of this proceeding.</P>
<P>4. I did not do so. I gave my evidence at trial as honestly and forthrightly as I could, to the best of my understanding of the question and recollection at the time.</P>
<P>5. I did not have and have no reason to lie or to favour David Long or Gerald Wright in the giving of my testimony. I had and have absolutely no financial interest in the outcome of this case. I have not been compensated in any way with respect to either agreeing to give evidence or in giving it.</P>
<P>6. I had relationships with both parties, over the years, sometimes friendly, and sometimes strained.</P>
<P>7. Mr. Wright and I did indeed engage in vituperative litigation, in the years 2002 to 2005, but, obviously, those facts were known to everybody. I was, in fact, cross-examined on that issue, to some extent, by the solicitor for the Defendants.</P>
<P>8. That litigation was satisfactorily settled by way of a confidential settlement agreement. In no way did my previous litigation with Mr. Wright influence my giving of evidence in this action. At all times I was truthful and was not motivated by any animosity arising from my dispute with Mr. Wright or any of the allegations made in my litigation with him.</P>
<P>9. In addition, certain motives were attributed to me by Mr. Wright in his evidence which were not never put to me in my cross-examination, so I was not given an opportunity to deny them, which I hereby do. Now produced and shown to me and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a copy of a transcript in that regard.</P>
<P>10. I became aware of this litigation, at the time it arose, as Mr. Long and I were engaged in business together with respect to certain potash projects in Thailand. That relationship was also disclosed in my evidence.</P>
<P>11. I felt at the time that, having been involved in the events giving rise to this litigation, after being asked by Mr. Long to provide my evidence, I felt that I had an obligation, simply as a person, to make my evidence available, so that any result of the litigation would be based on complete and truthful facts.</P>
<P>12. In fact, my wife and I had a severe disagreement over my getting involved. She told me she was frightened of Mr. Wright and what he might do in revenge for my testifying, and she urged me to stay out of things. I told her, and I still believe, that I had an obligation to make my knowledge available in the process.</P>
<P>13. As it turned out, I was never contacted by Mr. Wright or his solicitors to discuss what my evidence would be or what I would have to say. Had I been so contacted, I would have told them exactly what I said in evidence and answered any questions they asked. I had nothing to hide.</P>
<P>14. As indicated, I had been involved in litigation with Mr. Wright, and I knew him, therefore, in the conduct of litigation, to be aggressive. In addition, knowing what Mr. Wright had told me, I considered his position in the immediate action to be dishonest. I considered that Mr. Long was at a disadvantage in this litigation, not being aware of the documentary trail that existed and, as a result, I wanted to make sure that he was aware of all of the potential evidence that existed based upon what I considered to be the true facts.</P>
<P>15. It is alleged that I gave false and fraudulent evidence in the following respects:
<P1>(a) I gave evidence that I only discussed the litigation with Mr. Long or his lawyers in early 2012, prior to the commencement of the litigation;</P1>
<P1>(b) I gave evidence that I was unbiased, and had no interest in the litigation;</P1>
<P1>(c) I gave evidence that I was a reluctant witness; and</P1>
<P1>(d) I gave evidence that I did not provide assistance, financial or otherwise to Mr. Long in the litigation.</P1></P>
<P>16. Mr. Long and I began working together, following a chance meeting in 2011. Previously, I knew him only casually through Mr. Wright. At the time, I was engaged in a number of projects in the potash industry in Thailand.</P>
<P>17. Timing, politics, and other considerations made potash potentially very profitable in Thailand and at the time I was considering pursuing a number of potash projects in Thailand. As a result, I needed a professional with international administrative and management experience to be based in Bangkok and administer the various projects on behalf of the companies which owned them.</P>
<P>18. Mr. Long seemed, to me to be ideally suited for the project. Now produced and shown to me and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a copy of his Curriculum Vitae which he provided to me as our discussions progressed.</P>
<P>19. I reached an arrangement with Mr. Long, whereby he was paid varying amounts for his consulting and management services in Thailand. His basic pay was a consulting fee of $10,000 per month plus a monthly living allowance. That increased as further projects were added, by $2,500 per month, per project. I considered that those consulting fees were commensurate with what he would be doing for the companies, the responsibility he would have, and also in keeping with the market for such management services as an expatriate in Thailand.</P>
<P>20. I had also been involved in business with Mr. Wright at the time of the events giving rise to this litigation. He had told me that Mr. Long owned 50% of the royalty in question, on a number of occasions.</P>
<P>21. I had also been involved in giving instructions to Messrs. Faskens and Martineau in connection with certain transactions surrounding the royalty, namely the protection of the rights of the royalty holders and the renegotiation of the royalty agreement when Asia Pacific Resources was acquired by a Thai company.</P>
<P>22. While reluctant and apprehensive at the outset about being a witness, having been requested by Mr. Long, I was of the view that I would provide evidence given that I was directly and personally involved, in the matters giving rise to this litigation. I had discussed them with Mr. Wright, he had told me certain things about his intentions with his share of the royalty, including to gift half of it to Mr. Long. I understood he was structuring his affairs in such a way as to avoid paying income tax and to conceal his interest in the royalty from his wife, from whom he intended to leave.</P>
<P>23. Although I bear no animosity towards Mr. Wright, and we settled our litigation, I have, and I had, as a result of my dealings with him and what he had told me, a low opinion of what he was trying to do to Mr. Long. It was, and is my opinion, that Mr. Wright is a man of considerable wealth who could afford expensive and debilitating litigation in order to deny Mr. Long what I understood Mr. Wright had given him. In my experience and opinion, in litigation Mr. Wright had the ability to be manipulative and extremely aggressive.</P>
<P>24. Based on my knowledge of the facts, Mr. Wright's position that Mr. Long had no interest in the royalty was a total lie and a fabrication. It was my view, based on things said to me, and based on my personal involvement, that Mr. Long did indeed have a 50% interest in the royalty.</P>
<P>25. I was of the view that my knowledge would contribute to establishing the truth. I expected Mr. Wright would lie, about the agreements he made, and I felt that I had an obligation to contribute my evidence to enable the truth to be established.</P>
<P>26. I also felt that Mr. Long was inexperienced in Canadian litigation, and would be unprepared to deal with somebody as aggressive as Mr. Wright. I felt it proper to give him my information and my views, so he and his lawyers could consider as to how best to conduct themselves. In fact, Mr. Long's nativity about Canadian litigation is what led me to send him an email dated June 17, 2012, discussed below.</P>
<P>27. It is not true, as alleged in these proceedings, that I offered and provided assistance over the period from June 2012 to February 2013. In fact, to the best of my recollection, I was involved in this matter on four separate occasions: June 2012; December 2012; February 2013; and shortly prior to trial.</P>
<P>28. It is entirely and categorically untrue that I provided financial assistance, or that my companies did, by paying Mr. Long's legal fees. Mr. Long, who was neither a Canadian citizen nor a Canadian resident but was residing in Bangkok, did not have a bank account he could readily employ. As indicated, he was being paid $10,000 per month (plus a monthly living allowance), which I felt was an appropriate level of compensation.</P>
<P>29. I made an arrangement, therefore, with Mr. Long, that his fees would be deposited into a bank account in the name of my company, and that I would distribute funds from that account as he directed, by wire transfer or otherwise. Now produced and shown to me and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit are copies of various documents reflecting that arrangement.</P>
<P>30. Any funds paid to Clark Wilson or Fraser Litigation were paid from Mr. Long's remuneration on his written instructions. In fact, on Mr. Long's behalf, I sent money to various places, including to people and institutions in Ireland, to his sister and, occasionally, to Clark Wilson.</P>
<P>31. The money I sent was always Mr. Long's money, I simply sent it when and where he directed me to do so. I also always insisted that he pay any bank charges arising out of the arrangement which, as a result of proceeding in that fashion were often in the amount of several hundreds of dollars.</P>
<P>32. Any funds which were forwarded to Clark Wilson on the instructions of Mr. Long were Mr. Long's funds, representing fees paid to him under his contract with me and my companies. It is totally and absolutely untrue that I provided any financial assistance, paid any of his legal bills, or had any financial interest, involvement, or stake in this litigation or its outcome. Any and all funds provided from that bank account to Clark Wilson were Mr. Long's money, distributed as he directed.</P>
<P>33. I also stand by my assertion that I provided no assistance to Mr. Long in this litigation. I considered assistance, when I was asked that question, to be something concrete, such as the arranging for counsel, a contribution to legal fees, or, as was put to me in cross-examination, creating a job for Mr. Long so that he would have the wherewithal to fund this litigation.</P>
<P>34. I did not consider it providing assistance to Mr. Long to be a witness and, as a witness, to advise both he and his lawyers as to what my evidence was and as to what documents I was aware of, as a witness, which would be relevant to the litigation. In my view, that is the obligation of every witness, and I did not, and do not view that as providing assistance to Mr. Long in the litigation, but rather as doing my duty. I alluded to that view in my evidence at trial.</P>
<P>35. I certainly met with Mr. Long's lawyers to prepare my evidence both in June 2012, February 2013, in anticipation of a July 2013 trial date, and then again in March 2015, shortly before the actual trial in the matter. When we met, and prepared my evidence, we prepared with respect to the events relevant to the litigation. In meeting before trial, we reviewed various documents which had been produced in the litigation. We did not review any of the emails which have been attached to the affidavit of Tiffany Hambrook, we did not discuss events between us or between Mr. Long and I that had taken place in 2012 and early 2013, and we did not prepare any evidence with respect to communications I had had with Mr. Long or his lawyers prior to or during the course of the litigation.</P>
<P>36. When I first met with Mr. Long's lawyers in June 2012, provided them with copies of emails that I had in my possession that were relevant to Mr. Long's royalty claim, which documents were produced by Mr. Long in his list of documents. I also provided them with a sealed envelope that Mr. Long had asked me to give to them. To this day, I have no idea what was contained in that envelope that I gave to his lawyers.</P>
<P>37. Accordingly, when I was questioned in those areas, based upon my understanding of what was being asked of me, I gave my answers to the best of my recollection and belief, but without any review of the events themselves having taken place.</P>
<P>38. As indicated, to the best of my recollection, I was not involved in this matter over the period of June 2012 to February 2013 as alleged. In fact, I was involved in this matter, prior to trial and preparation for trial, only on the three occasions referred to in paragraph 27: June 2012, December 2012 and February 2013.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>JUNE OF 2012</UNDER>:</TI>
<P>39. In the period between June 17, 2012, and June 30, 2012, I met with Mr. Long's lawyers, I met with the Andersons, I provided certain emails to Mr. Long's lawyers, and I sent my lengthy email of June 17, 2012.</P>
<P>40. When I gave my evidence, I said that I had met with Mr. Long's lawyer and discussed matters with Mr. Long prior to the commencement of proceedings. In reviewing the record, it appears that my recollection at trial was in error as I have since been shown that the proceedings were commenced in April, and I have viewed my June 17 email which contains comments on the pleadings.</P>
<P>41. My recollection as to timing was incorrect, but that was my memory at the time. Indeed, I had forgotten, when I gave my evidence, even sending the June 17 email. I had never discussed it with anyone, including Mr. Long. I did not provide it to Clark Wilson, and I did not discuss it with them when we met.</P>
<P>42. In addition, at the time of my cross-examination, my understanding of what counsel for Mr. Wright meant when he referred to the &ldquo;commencement of proceedings&rdquo; was a bit vague. As I alluded to in my June 17 email, my view is that there is a process of the discovery of facts and documents, following which a decision is made as to whether or not to go to trial, and that is when the litigation truly gets underway or commences. Plus, the proceeding of the trial, which is what I had understood he was referring to, had been ongoing for several days before I took the stand.</P>
<P>43. My appreciation for what was meant by the term &ldquo;proceeding&rdquo; aside, although I now see that I had my meetings after the filing of the pleadings, I still have a recollection of discussing with Mr. Long starting the lawsuit prior to him doing so, but I can see from emails that I must be mistaken.</P>
<P>44. By the time of the trial, my contact with Clark Wilson was over two years earlier. I had not reviewed these documents or emails dealing with those matters, and my memory was vague. I answered the questions I was asked to the best of my ability and as honestly as I could. Very specific questions were asked which I answered to the best of my ability. If my memory is correct, I had a discussion with Mr. Long prior to him starting his lawsuit. At no time did I say this was the only time I had discussed the lawsuit with Mr. Long or his lawyers.</P>
<P>45. In any event, during that June period, I met with Ms. Tribe. I volunteered that information at trial.</P>
<P>46. Before March 2015, Ms. Tribe and I only met on June 18, 2012 and then had a follow up conversation by phone. I also met with Ms. Anna Sekunova in February 2013.</P>
<P>47. During that time period, being June 2012, at their request, I also met with Alice Anderson, and her brother-in-law David, who is a lawyer and was assisting Ms. Anderson in relation to her royalty interest. Her husband Bob had died, and, accordingly, I met with Alice and her brother-in-law. I also referred to that meeting in my evidence.</P>
<P>48. I did not say that I had obtained the emails myself because I was not asked whether I had. I did not obtain any other documents from Faskens Martineau, but left that up to Mr. Long and his lawyers.</P>
<P>49. In my evidence, I did not mention the email of June 17, 2012 and I did not specifically recall it. In addition, I was not asked about the further dates and nature of my communications with Mr. Long in relation to this litigation. As I said, I have never discussed it with anyone, however, if I had been asked if I had further communications with Mr. Long, after early 2012, I would have confirmed that I had. In addition, this email was not fresh in my memory as it was not discussed at any of my meetings with Clark Wilson, Fraser Litigation Group or with Mr. Long.</P>
<P>50. As stated above, I considered Mr. Long to be naive insofar as Canadian litigation was concerned. When he informed me that he has commenced his claim, he told me that he anticipated the resolution of the matter to be a relatively simple process. Specifically, he told me that he thought he would simply be required to swear and affidavit and that the true ownership of the royalty would be determined by the court on a simple application. As a result, I felt compelled to warn him about what to expect from the Canadian litigation process.</P>
<P>51. The email is lengthy as I wanted to ensure that Mr. Long not only knew what my evidence was, but that he was sufficiently warned about the endeavour that he was embarking upon. As a result, I drafted this email to provide Mr. Long with all my thoughts on the events and on Mr. Wright, and how he conducted litigation, so that Mr. Long and his lawyers, without me, could make what use of it they wished. These words were simply my thoughts on how the litigation might unfold and my suggestions of how I might approach the litigation, no more and no less.</P>
<P>52. I did not follow it up, I did not raise the email or its suggestions with anyone and until this application, I did not even know Mr. Long had forwarded it to his lawyers. From the emails produced, I can see that he did so in February of 2013.</P>
<P>53. I also note that at paragraph 21(a) of the memorandum of argument filed by Mr. Wright's lawyer in this appeal that it is alleged that I stated that: &ldquo;it was the task of David Long and Darch to &ldquo;jointly&rdquo; educate the plaintiff's lawyers on the points set out in Darch's email.&rdquo; This is simply a misreading of my email as I specifically stated: &ldquo;It is not possible so <UNDER>you</UNDER> must educate <UNDER>them</UNDER> [being his lawyers] and then &ldquo;jointly&rdquo; <UNDER>you and they</UNDER> have to filter out those that support your case. At no time did I suggest that I would be involved in any capacity other than to provide evidence as a witness.</P>
<P>54. Similarly, in paragraph 21(h) of the memorandum of argument, Mr. Wright and his counsel misconstrue both the contents and intent of my statement wherein I stated that I had to be the last witness and &ldquo;the one who ties a bow on the case.&rdquo; As the paragraph continues, because of my previous disputes with Mr. Wright, I did not feel that my evidence alone would prove Mr. Long's case and that he could only rely on me being a truthful witness to corroborate what Mr. Long would have to prove through documents and otherwise.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>DECEMBR OF 2012:</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. I was not involved again until five and a half months later, in December of 2012. On the 21<SUP>st</SUP> of December, I reviewed documents from the List of Documents, provided to me by Clark Wilson. The same day I replied referring to one document. I do not recall what that document said, and I do not recall what documents I reviewed or who made arrangements for me to do so.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>FEBRUARY OF 2013:</UNDER></TI>
<P>56. The third occasion of my involvement was in an exchange of emails between February 19 and 25<SUP>th</SUP>, 2013, which emails were sent at the verbal request of Ms. Anna Sekunova, counsel for Mr. Long at that time. The email of February 19<SUP>th</SUP>, provided information about the value of royalty for potash, so Mr. Long would not be fooled into thinking it was worthless. The email of February 25 provided information relevant to my relationship with Mr. Wright, as I said in that email &ldquo;as I may be called upon to be a witness.&rdquo; If I was going to testify, I felt Mr. Long's lawyer should be aware of matters as to my relationship with Mr. Wright, upon which I expected I would be cross-examined. I did not discuss either of those emails with anyone, that I recall, although I discussed these matters as well, in 2015, when preparing for trial.</P>
<P>57. Indeed, February of 2013, was my last involvement until just prior to trial in March 2015. I met with Mr. Long's lawyers to prepare my evidence and I had a number of phone calls.</P>
<P>58. I had not seen Mr. Long since April 2014, when we parted ways in our business. I made it clear, when I telephoned Ms. Tribe, to discuss giving my evidence, that I would only testify if I was under subpoena. That insistence was as a result of a further conversation with my wife, and I felt it was prudent. I had no interest in the outcome of the litigation, and thought it would be appropriate for me to be subpoenaed.</P>
<P>59. When I testified, while I had prepared on the merits of the issues, I had not prepared at all on issues of my contacts between Mr. Long, me, and his lawyer, two years earlier. I gave my evidence as truthfully as I could.</P>
<P>60. If my evidence was mistaken, such mistakes were inadvertent. I gave my evidence as honestly as I could, based on what I then recalled.</P>
<P>61. I understood my role was to answer questions, not to argue, not to volunteer information, and not to try to persuade, but simply to answer the precise questions asked of me as simply as possible, and that is what I attempted to do.</P>
<P>
