<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. <UNDER>Position Statement of the Respondent</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. This is an application to introduce fresh evidence, and essentially set aside both a trial judgment, and a judgment of this Court due to alleged perjury, or fraud. When such issues arise, the law strives to maintain a tension between its need for finality in its determinations, and a need to protect its processes from fraudulent abuse.</P>
<P>2. This Application and these Appellants are precisely the type of litigant and Application against which, in resolving that tension, the court tries to guard. The Appellants Wright has a history of aggressive litigation, and excessive and scandalous allegations. Such allegations have, in fact, earmarked his positions in this case.</P>
<P>3. The law has developed a test to ensure that both the need for finality and the need to prevent abuse are weighed and considered on applications of this nature. The test is as follows:
<P1>(a) The Appellants must establish perjury, on a balance of probabilities;</P1>
<P1>(b) It is actual perjury that must be established, which is the deliberate giving of false evidence with the intent to mislead the court, not simply inaccuracies or mistakes in evidence;</P1>
<P1>(c) The Appellants may not raise any such allegations about which he knew at the time of trial, or about which he ought to have known with the appropriate exercise of due diligence; and</P1>
<P1>(d) The allegations, if established, must be as to evidence which was material to the decision in question.</P1></P>
<P>4. This application fails to meet all four grounds of the test.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. <UNDER>Facts</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. The Applicant applies to introduce fresh evidence and to set aside the decision of this Honourable Court made July 12, 2017. The fresh evidence, it is said, discloses perjury on behalf of both the Plaintiff, David P. Long, and a witness called on his behalf, one John Darch. The perjury which is claimed focuses on the degree of involvement of Mr. Darch in assisting the Plaintiff with his case. It is claimed that the fresh evidence will show:
<P1>(a) Mr. Darch and the Plaintiff lied about whether financial assistance was provided by Mr. Darch by way of the payment of the legal fees of the Plaintiff; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Darch and the Plaintiff lied about Mr. Darch providing assistance to the Plaintiff and his lawyers with respect to the conduct of the litigation.</P1></P>
<P>6. It is the position of the Plaintiff that the fresh evidence ought not to be permitted. Perjured evidence is evidence given, knowing it to be false, in order to mislead the court. Perjured evidence does not consist of answers to questions which are less than perfect, or which are less than perfectly accurate in all particulars. It is acknowledged that witnesses make mistakes, that memories get confused, that distant events are difficult to recall, and that such evidence, while suffering from frailty, is neither perjury, nor fraud.</P>
<P>7. The evidence reveals in fact that those witnesses disclosed, in their testimony, many of the facts, of which the Appellants now claim they were ignorant. Moreover, the Appellants must be taken to know that witnesses to be called by the opposing party routinely discuss matters with that party or their lawyers, provide or review documents with them, summarize their evidence, and prepare to give testimony.</P>
<P>8. As will be discussed later, the fact that Mr. Darch was going to testify was disclosed on a number of occasions to the Defendant but the Defendant chose not to interview him, not to discuss with him what evidence he might give, and did not pursue the matters of which he now complains to have been unaware on discovery.</P>
<P>9. In any event, the essential finding of the trial judge, that Mr. Darch did not have an interest in the litigation is unassailable. A determination of credibility depends on a whole host of factors. To the extent there are some minor inaccuracies in the evidence of Mr. Darch and the Plaintiff, those are not sufficient to have any effect on the basic decision as to credibility, preferring the evidence of and on behalf of the Plaintiff, in its totality, to that of the Defendant.</P>
<P>10. In their Memorandum of Argument, the Appellants point to:
<P1>(a) A number of documents indicating Mr. Darch or his companies appear to have been paying the Plaintiff's legal fees;</P1>
<P1>(b) A number of emails in the period of June 12, to June 30, 2012, in which Mr. Darch discussed and forwarded certain documents to the Plaintiff's lawyers and discussed both the case and his evidence;</P1>
<P1>(c) The forwarding of some documents to Mr. Darch, by the lawyers for the Plaintiff, in December 2012, for his review; and</P1>
<P1>(d) Two emails in February, 2013, discussing the value of the royalty at issue in the proceedings, and discussing attacks the Plaintiff would make upon Mr. Darch.</P1></P>
<P>11. In terms of the alleged payment of legal fees by Mr. Darch, the allegation of the Appellants is simply untrue. In terms of the emails of June, December, and February, the Appellants do not assert that if the contents of the emails dealing with the merits had been revealed, that would have affected the outcome. In fact, the contents of the emails, in so far as they touch on the merits, are consistent with the evidence of Mr. Darch and the Plaintiff, and are consistent with the findings of the learned trial judge. Rather, it is the fact alone of the emails that the Appellants claim supports the allegation of perjury or fraud which would change the outcome of the case. That this so is said to be because of these findings:
<P1>(a) Findings of the trial judge;
<QUOTE><P>[47] Mr. John Darch, who was a long-time business associate of Mr. Wright and a fellow Royalty holder testified that he knew that Mr. Wright was appointing Mr. Long as his nominee for the royalty and that he clearly told Mr. Darch that he was sharing this royalty with Mr. Long. Mr. Darch also said that Mr. Wright told him that he would rather receive half of the royalty than one quarter, the reason being that he would lose half to Canada Revenue Agency and he would have to share the other half with his wife Gail whom he was planning to leave for his Thai mistress. Mr. Darch said that Mr. Wright told him this on more than one occasion.</P>
<P>[50] Mr. Darch is a neutral witness, having no bias in favour of either of the parties. He has no financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.</P>
<P>&ldquo;[57] On the evidence, I think Mr. Long's version of events is more probable.</P></QUOTE>
<P2>1) The representation of a beneficial 50:50 share of the royalty is consistent with the past friendship and financial business relationship of the parties.</P2>
<P2>2) Despite being warned by Mr. Darch about &ldquo;properly papering&rdquo;, the true nature of a shared 50:50 interest arrangement in the royalty transfer to Mr. Long, Mr. Wright chose not to leave a paper trail, ostensibly for personal domestic and taxation reasons. Mr. Darch in effect corroborated Mr. Long's assertion that Mr. Wright initially preferred a &ldquo;better a half than ultimately a quarter&rdquo; interest in the royalty.</P2>
<P2>3) Although Mr. Wright is a sophisticated and experienced businessman, he chose not to leave a traceable paper trail about the true nature of the transfer. He was concerned about potential taxation consequences if the true nature of the transfer was papered. However, he could also have effected a private declaration of trust document between himself and Mr. Long, known only between themselves.&rdquo;</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) Findings of the Court of Appeal.
<QUOTE><P>[31] John Darch described himself as a businessman. He was closely associated with Wright at the time the royalty interest was acquired and then transferred to Long. While Darch subsequently had a falling out with Wright and was involved in acrimonious litigation with him and thereafter hired Long as a consultant, he denied counsel's suggestion that his testimony was motivated by animosity toward Wright. He denied any interest in the outcome of the litigation. The trial judge, having had the advantage of taking the measure of the witness, found, at para. 50:</P>
<P>Mr. Darch is a neutral witness, having no bias in favour of either of the parties. He has no financial interest in the outcome of this litigation.</P></QUOTE></P1></P>
<P>12. The determination of credibility was based on a number of facts as found by the Learned Trial Judge:
<P1>(a) Mr. Long received a share of 50% of settlement proceeds from aggressive litigation conducted in Ireland, even though entirely paid for by Mr. Wright, indicating their business relationship;</P1>
<P1>(b) The oral 50/50 arrangements as to the royalty reflected the close business relationship between Mr. Wright and Mr. Long;</P1>
<P1>(c) Mr. Wright did not reveal any personal interest in the royalty, to Faskens Martineau DuMoulin LLP (&ldquo;Faskens&rdquo;) and, in fact purported to be acting as the agent for Mr. Long, Fasken's named client;</P1>
<P1>(d) Mr. Wright provided information to Mr. Long which would be relevant only to an owner of an interest in the royalty;</P1>
<P1>(e) Mr. Darch was a neutral witness, having no bias in favour of either of the parties, with no financial interest in the outcome of the litigation;</P1>
<P1>(f) Mr. Anderson confirmed that Mr. Wright had told him that Mr. Long owned the royalty and that he was acting only as Mr. Long's agent;</P1>
<P1>(g) Mr. Wright gave similar advice to Mr. Gabrielson and Mark Andrews, Q.C.</P1></P>
<P>13. In the end, the Learned Trial Judge concluded that Mr. Long's version of events was more probable than Mr. Wright's in as much as:
<P1>(a) It &ldquo;was consistent with the past friendship and the business relationship&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Wright created no documents to reflect the arrangements he claimed existed, despite being a sophisticated and experienced businessman; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Mr. Darch corroborated Mr. Long's assertion that the structure was set up by Mr. Wright to conceal true ownership, in order to avoid domestic issues and tax consequences.</P1></P>
<P>14. This Honourable Court made the following findings:
<P1>(a) The Learned Trial Judge accepted Mr. Long's evidence;</P1>
<P1>(b) The Learned Trial Judge referred to accepting Mr. Darch's evidence that he had advised Mr. Wright to paper the transaction;</P1>
<P1>(c) The Learned Trial Judge relied on the various lawyer's evidence;</P1>
<P1>(d) With respect to Mr. Darch, having had the advantage of taking the measure of the witness, the learned trial judge found him credible;</P1>
<P1>(e) Mr. Darch denied any animosity towards Mr. Wright;</P1>
<P1>(f) Mr. Darch denied any interest in the outcome of the litigation; and</P1>
<P1>(g) Mr. Darch's evidence was not dis-similar to that of Mr. Royce, Mr. Wright's accountant.</P1></P>
<P>15. In his special costs decision, Mr. Justice Wong found Mr. Wright's conduct was reprehensible and deserving of rebuke on the basis, that:
<P1>(a) His conduct pre-litigation in denying the trust arrangement was a fraud;</P1>
<P1>(b) He alleged that Mr. Long commenced the action as a means of engaging in a campaign of harassment;</P1>
<P1>(c) His defence was without merit and constituted obfuscation of the major issues;</P1>
<P1>(d) He put forward a self-serving story, coupled with character aspersions which were reprehensible.</P1></P>
<P>16. Those aspersions continue, and it is now alleged that both Mr. Long and Mr. Darch, the independent witness, are perjurers.</P>
<P>17. These allegations are equally reprehensible, and equally without merit as those hurled at the Plaintiff at trial.</P>
<P>18. The present application arises as a result of the special costs award. The decision of this court in <CASEREF><SOC>Guchuru v. Smith</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 414</CITE></CASEREF>, holds that, in order to maintain a special costs award, the entirety of the lawyer's file must be produced. The court says, in that decision, that a litigant can avoid the obvious problems arising from that waiver of privilege by waiting until all appeal rights have been exhausted before revealing his/her file.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Guchuru v. Smith</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 414</CITE><PARANUM>104 and 114</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>19. Ironically, the Appellants have now seized upon certain contents of that file to bring these very serious allegations.</P>
<P>20. The trial was lengthy. It occupied 16 days. The court heard evidence from Mr. Wright and Mr. Long, from Mr. Darch, from Mark Andrews, Q.C., from Mr. Gabrielson, also of Faskens, and from David Anderson, another lawyer. All of them corroborated Mr. Long, while the evidence provided by Paul Royce, an accountant, called by Mr. Wright, was found to dove tail with that of Mr. Darch. It was not inconsistent with that of Mr. Long.</P>
<P>21. It must also be remembered that both Mr. Darch and Mr. Wright, and Mr. Darch and Mr. Long, had complicated relationship histories of their own.</P>
<P>22. Mr. Long and Mr. Wright were lifelong friends until an ugly falling out in 2011. Mr. Darch and Mr. Wright had been long time business partners and were so at the time of the events giving rise to this litigation. They also had an ugly falling out, which ended in vituperative litigation. Mr. Wright accused Mr. Darch of fraud. Obviously, all of that was well known to Mr. Wright.</P>
<P>23. Mr. Darch and Mr. Long also had been in business together, and like Mr. Darch and Mr. Wright, had been friends. They too had parted ways. Unlike Mr. Wright, the two had not sued each other, but they terminated their relationship in 2014, a year prior to trial, and had not spoken since. All of that was also known to Mr. Wright.</P>
<P>24. That being the case, when advised in June 2013 by Mr. Long's Trial Brief, upon being advised again, in March 2015 by Mr. Long's second Trial Brief, followed by the providing of a Will Say statement, of the fact that Mr. Darch would be a witness for the Plaintiff, the remarkable fact is that neither Mr. Wright or his counsel contacted Mr. Darch or even, attempted to do so to discuss what evidence he would give. That remarkable fact is only exceeded by the even more remarkable assertion, crucial on this application, that Mr. Wright could not have discovered, prior to trial, what Mr. Darch's evidence was, what evidence he had to give and what his involvement was,.</P>
<P>25. The Appellants' version of the facts and their attack on Mr. Darch overstate the true facts. The Appellants rely on what they say are two essential facts. (para 33, para 19).
<QUOTE><P>33. In addition to the significant assistance provided Darch as outlined above, a number of emails in the plaintiff's solicitors' file establish that Darch made several direct, and indirect payments through his company Western Investments Ltd., towards the plaintiff's legal accounts.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Affidavit of Tiffany Hambrook, Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;, pp. 4&ndash;12</P1>
<QUOTE><P>19. The solicitors' file is replete with evidence that Darch and the plaintiff discussed the litigation in detail orally and by way of correspondence over at least the period of January 2012 to February 2013. We have reviewed a portion of that evidence below, which can be described as nothing less than remarkable given the testimony of Darch and the plaintiff.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Appellants' Memorandum of Argument, paras. 33 and 19</P1></P>
<P>26. The first is untrue, the latter is wildly overstated.</P>
<P>27. As to the latter, in the first place, the documents produced do not disclose that Mr. Darch and the Plaintiff discussed the litigation in detail both orally and by way of correspondence as the Appellants allege. In the second place, such correspondence as there was, does not disclose a continuous involvement of Mr. Darch in the litigation from June 2012 to February 2013. That is a total mischaracterization of the evidence.</P>
<P>28. In fact, there were four distinct periods of involvement on the part of Mr. Darch: June 2012, a couple of days in December 2012, and two emails from Mr. Darch to Mr. Long's lawyers in February 2013. In addition, of course, Mr. Darch was involved in preparing for trial in March 2015, two years after the last of those events.</P>
<P>29. In so far as financial assistance is concerned, the allegations that Mr. Darch paid legal accounts are simply untrue. The basic facts are that Mr. Long, as was well known to Mr. Wright, worked for Mr. Darch in Bangkok. He earned upwards of $10,000 per month, plus a living allowance. As a matter of convenience to Mr. Long, those funds were deposited into and disbursed from a bank account in the name of Western Investments Ltd., Mr. Darch's company.</P>
<P>30. Payments went from that account to organizations and institutions, to relatives, and, on occasion, to Mr. Long's lawyers. Mr. Long was charged with the bank fees for this arrangement which were, after all, made for his convenience. All of the money provided to Clark Wilson LLP, whether by transfer or by cheque, delivered by Mr. Darch, was Mr. Long's money. Neither Mr. Darch, nor Mr. Darch acting through any of his companies provided any financial assistance at all to Mr. Long. The allegation is simply untrue.</P>
<P>31. The other allegation, that of providing assistance, is more nebulous. Certainly Mr. Darch provided information and expressed his views of how Mr. Wright might conduct the litigation. If the providing of information is the providing of &ldquo;assistance&rdquo; in the sense that indicates a disqualifying bias, then virtually every non-party witness is guilty.</P>
<P>32. At trial, Mr. Darch said with respect to the providing of information the following:
<QUOTE><P>A: I have not been assisting Mr. Long in the litigation. I gave him this information at the time, that if he was being denied something which he claimed was justly his, then it would be inappropriate of me not to tell him where he might find the proof that he needs.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Appellants' Memorandum, pg. 6</P1></P>
<P>33. It is necessary to turn to the evidence of what the Appellants say was evidence of the providing of assistance in a disqualifying way with precision and care, and not with a generalized gloss. One must closely examine the evidence in support of each accusation:
<P1>(a) Mr. Darch sent a lengthy email on June 17, 2012, to Mr. Long. Mr. Long did not share that memo with his lawyers until February of 2013. There is no indication that they discussed it, or that Mr. Darch knew what Mr. Long had done with the email and he swears he did not;</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Darch met with Mr. Long's lawyers on June 18, 2012, to discuss his evidence;</P1>
<P1>(c) Mr. Darch sent emails on June 28, 2012, surrounding his meetings with the Andersons, who had requested him to meet to discuss the litigation;</P1>
<P1>(d) On June 30, 2012, Mr. Darch sent an email regarding a visit he had made to Faskens to review the royalty files in which Faskens had been involved; and</P1>
<P1>(e) He provided certain source document emails to Long's lawyers, which were disclosed in long's List of Documents.</P1></P>
<P>34. Mr. Darch gave evidence that his involvement in the above matters occurred before the pleadings commenced. His timing may have been off. The proceedings were commenced in April, not June. In his affidavit, Mr. Darch asserts that he still has a recollection of discussing the case prior to the proceedings with Long, as he testified he had at trial. With this said, however, even if his recollection is incorrect, and he did not have any discussions prior to April, this was a mistake on his part, not a knowing lie made with the intention to mislead the court.</P>
<P>35. At paragraph 4 of the Appellants' Memorandum of Argument, it is contended that it was Mr. Darch's testimony at trial that he &ldquo;only discussed the litigation with the plaintiff in early 2012, prior to the commencement of the litigation&rdquo;. This was absolutely not so.</P>
<P>36. A careful analysis of the cross examination of Mr. Darch shows that he was asked very specific questions and provided truthful answers to same. Specifically, he was asked if he had ever &ldquo;discussed&rdquo; the legal proceeding with Mr. Long, to which he advised that he had. When asked about when these discussions took place, he advised that they were in the early part of 2012. It was then put to him if he had discussed the matter with Long before he initiated the proceedings, with which Mr. Darch agreed. No further questions were asked. At no time did Mr. Darch state or suggest that this was the only time he had talked to Mr. Long about this litigation.</P>
<P>37. Of the above list of events occurring in June, 2012, all but the email of June 17 were disclosed by Mr. Darch in his evidence at trial:
<ITEM><P>Mr. Darch discussed the case with Mr. Long (pg. 580);</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Mr. Darch met with the lawyers (pg. 580);</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Mr. Darch met with the Andersons (pg. 581);</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Mr. Darch provided documents, being emails to the lawyers, (pg. 580 and 581).</P></ITEM></P>
<P>38. These facts were not probed in cross-examination. They were not in fact even followed up on, but they were, nonetheless, revealed. The contents of the lawyer's file, and the emails relied on by the Appellants, while fleshing things out somewhat, all, with the exception of the email of June 17<SUP>th</SUP> reflect events specifically disclosed at the trial and do not constitute fresh evidence at all. The fact they were virtually ignored in cross-examination does not make them so.</P>
<P>39. Moreover, none of the documents, again with the exception of the email of June 17, indicates that Mr. Darch was particularly involved with Mr. Long and the litigation. What they do show is an interchange of information between the lawyers and Mr. Darch, much like one would expect from any witness with contemporaneous knowledge of the events. The only matter, therefore, of which the Appellants complain in June and which was not specifically and actually known by them, is the email of June 17.</P>
<P>40. That email does not show that Mr. Darch discussed the case with Mr. Long. The email was never discussed between the two men, and nor does it seem to have had much significance to Mr. Long. He did not even forward it to his lawyers until February of 2013. Moreover, it is not the contents of the email going to the merits which lead the Appellants to say Mr. Darch committed perjury.</P>
<P>41. The contents concerning the merits are consistent with Mr. Darch's evidence, and contain certain relevant assertions with respect to their truth. It also contains Mr. Darch's view of the timing of the commencement of proceedings.
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Tiffany Hambrook, Exhibit B, pg. 21</P1></P>
<P>42. Mr. Darch swears, in paras. 24 through 26 of his affidavit, that his experience with Mr. Wright suggested he would both lie and misconduct himself in the litigation. In order to ensure the truth came out, he felt he had to pass on both his knowledge, and to warn Mr. Long as to how Mr. Wright would conduct himself. He predicted, accurately. Mr. Wright lied numerous times at the trial, made reprehensible allegations, and employed such tactics as not listing relevant documents until after his examination for discovery.</P>
<P>43. With respect to paragraph 21(a) of the Memorandum, as set out in Mr. Darch's affidavit, the Appellants completely misquote and misconstrue the contents of the email. At no time does Mr. Darch suggest that he is to educate the plaintiff's lawyers, and, instead, he states that it will be up to Mr. Long to educate his own lawyers on matters.</P>
<P>44. Similarly, paragraph 21(h) of the Memorandum is a complete misrepresentation of the intent of the statement in that paragraph of the email. Mr. Darch is not suggesting that he will be the key to winning the case. To the contrary, he is stating that Mr. Long will have to prove the case absent his testimony and, given his previous history with Mr. Wright and the anticipated attacks on his motive at trial, that he will only be able to corroborate the evidence in place.</P>
<P>45. It is in essence the fact of the email that is claimed to be perjury with respect to the denial that Mr. Darch provided assistance. Mr. Darch maintained, both at trial, and still maintains, that as that term was understood by him, he did not in fact provide assistance. It is that assertion which is said to constitute perjury. It does not. Both Mr. Darch and Mr. Long have testified that they had forgotten about the email by the time of trial. They had not prepared for trial on the issue of the involvement of Mr. Darch in trial preparation, or their communications with each other. The June 2012 events had taken place almost three years prior to trial. Not surprisingly, their actual preparation had focused on the events, not their dealings inter se.</P>
<P>46. Moreover, while potentially inaccurate on timing, Mr. Darch did say he had discussed the lawsuit with Mr. Long prior to litigation commencing, which may, instead, have been in June of 2012. Not only is it very likely that Mr. Darch did discuss the litigation with Mr. Long prior to April 2012, but he was not asked if he had communicated further with Long about it. He was not asked about follow up discussions, the content of those discussions, or whether he had sent Mr. Long any emails. Once again, the evidence he gave was neither probed, nor tested, nor even expanded upon in cross-examination.</P>
<P>47. The failure to mention the sending of a forgotten email when not specifically asked, all the while admitting that he had discussed the case with Mr. Long, does not even approximate the serious conduct which would support an accusation of perjury. It must also be remembered that the denial of any friendship was, at the time of trial, also true. Mr. Darch and Mr. Long may have been associates and business friends in 2012, but they were no longer so by trial. They had not even seen each other for a year.</P>
<P>48. In so far as Mr. Long is concerned, at trial he denied any discussions with Mr. Darch. That was inconsistent with Mr. Darch's evidence. That provided an ample opportunity for Mr. Wright to probe that inconsistency. The argument that Mr. Long gave a false answer in that regard does not arise from a review of the file and is not fresh evidence&mdash;the contradiction and the error in his evidence were not only known, but Mr. Wright failed to explore and exploit that contradiction in cross.</P>
<P>49. There was no further contact from Mr. Darch after June 2012 for another 5 <TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC> months. In December 2012, there was an exchange of emails between Clark Wilson and Darch and a review of some documents by Darch. That occurred over the period of a day or two. Whether it is perjury not to reveal that specific exchange of emails without actually being asked, again, goes to whether those events should have been recalled at all, whether they constitute assistance in some sort of disqualifying way, or could not have been known to Mr. Wright.</P>
<P>50. Frankly, it must be expected that counsel will provide documents from a List of Documents to contemporaneous witnesses and seek their comments. All lawyers do that, and all witnesses invariably cooperate. Nothing sinister arises out of such conduct on the part of a cooperating witness. If that is seen as a form of disqualifying assistance, than virtually all third party witnesses are suspect.</P>
<P>51. The same can be said of the two emails in February 2013. The first was a result of a request from counsel on a matter on which Mr. Darch was knowledgeable, the second consisted of delineating areas in which Mr. Darch felt he was likely to be attacked by Mr. Wright.</P>
<P>52. Again the question comes down to determining whether that constitutes the providing of assistance. Whatever that may actually mean (absent financial assistance) Mr. Wright was a very experienced litigant, represented by experienced and competent counsel. He cannot seriously contend that he took the denial that Mr. Darch had provided assistance to mean he had not discussed documents and evidence with Long's counsel. He cannot deny that that activity in fact is to be expected of every witness. The Appellants cannot seriously contend that discussing documents and evidence with counsel who is calling a witness, constitutes the providing of &ldquo;assistance&rdquo; so as to render perjurous a denial of doing so.</P>
<P>53. Mr. Darch swears that he did not consider that conduct to be providing assistance. Given that it would be normal to discuss evidence and documents, if the Appellants wished that term to be interpreted as denying normal and expected conduct. It was incumbent upon them to specifically put those propositions and narrow that term in cross-examination.</P>
<P>54. Mr. Darch testified:
<QUOTE><P>The Witness: Then my response will be to this, My Lord, absolutely I did not hire Mr. Long for any purpose of pursuing any claim against Mr. Wright. That is absolutely not in my interest. I have no interest who wins, friendship-wise, business-wise, any other reason. So whatever you may be trying to suggest over and over again is simply not true.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>55. That evidence was true. Mr. Darch had no interest in the litigation. By the time of trial he had no friendship with Mr. Long or Mr. Wright. He was a reluctant witness, as confirmed on several occasions.</P>
<P>56. With respect to Mr. Darch's reluctance to act as a witness, the Appellants fail to reference the communications in which this fact was relayed. On June 18, 2012, Mr. Long spoke of Mr. Darch, stating: &ldquo;He will also be a very advantageous, if somewhat reluctant, witness should we go to court.&rdquo; Mr. Darch's reluctance was again relayed in his March 2015 communications with legal counsel wherein he requested a &ldquo;summon to appear as a witness&rdquo; and stated he was certain that Mr. Wright's lawyer would try to sabotage him and allege he was acting out of revenge. In this exchange, he confirmed that he had &ldquo;no vested interest in whoever wins the case&rdquo;. Of note, although disclosed to them, the Appellants did not include this email exchange in the affidavit of Tiffany Hambrook.</P>
<P>57. In addition, of all the emails, only the June 17 email, and the brief exchanges of emails in December and February constituted events which were not specifically disclosed in Mr. Darch's evidence at trial.</P>
<P>58. It is perhaps telling that the Appellants have been somewhat selective even now in their production from counsels' file.</P>
<P>59. The Appellants are hard pressed to say that they could not have known of the events reflected in those emails or could not have discovered them with due diligence, because they never asked. The Appellants are equally hard pressed to say they honestly believed that when Mr. Darch said he was not providing assistance, particularly as that answer was qualified, it is perjury if he had, in fact, discussed documents and his evidence with counsel.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. <UNDER>The Law</UNDER></TI>
<P>60. While the test for introducing fresh evidence is tailored somewhat in a distinctive way in cases in which it is alleged the fresh evidence discloses that the judgment was obtained by fraud or perjury, the starting point of any fresh analysis is <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Palmer</SOC></CASEREF>, (citation).</P>
<P>61. At page 775, the court lays down four principles:
<QUOTE><P>(1) The evidence should generally not be admitted if, by due diligence, it could have been adduced at trial provided that this general principle will not be applied as strictly in a criminal case as in civil cases: see <CASEREF><SOC>McMartin v. the Queen</SOC></CASEREF></P>
<P>(2) The evidence must be relevant in the sense that it bears upon a decisive or potentially decisive issue in the trial.</P>
<P>(3) The evidence must be credible in the sense that it is reasonably capable of belief, and</P>
<P>(4) It must be such that if believed it could reasonably, when taken with the other evidence adduced at trial, be expected to have affected the result.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ascent Developments Corp. v. Stonehenge Projects Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 287</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>HMTQ v. N.L.P</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 773</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>62. Here, it is claimed, the fresh evidence whose introduction is sought will show that certain evidence given at trial was fraudulent in that it was perjured testimony. It is alleged that the fresh evidence will show that the witness Mr. Darch perjured himself when he testified:
<P1>(a) He had not provided assistance to the Plaintiff;</P1>
<P1>(b) He had no bias as between the Plaintiff and the Defendant; and</P1>
<P1>(c) He had no interest in the outcome of the litigation.</P1></P>
<P>63. It is also claimed that the Plaintiff perjured himself when he testified he had not discussed the case with Mr. Darch.</P>
<P>64. Perjury is an extremely serious allegation. It has three elements&mdash;falsity, knowledge and intent. In order to establish perjury the evidence must establish not only that the evidence was false. It must also be established that the witness knew that the evidence was false, and, further, that that knowingly false evidence was given in order to mislead the court.</P>
<P>65. The key elements are the knowledge that the evidence is false and the intent to mislead. In <EM>Granitile</EM>, the court acknowledged that a determination that certain evidence or that a certain witness lacks credibility is not the same as finding the evidence was perjured. The court acknowledged that false or untrue evidence might be given as a result of:
<QUOTE><P>[465] I should also note that the finding that perjury was not present does not detract from the fact that Nicholas Pirruccio was not accurate, honest or complete in what he told the Court. There were things he should have said that he did not. Counsel for the plaintiffs submitted that: &ldquo;it is beyond debate that false testimony provided as a result of confusion, mistake, faulty memory, carelessness, misunderstanding, mistaken conclusions, unjustified inferences testifies to negligently, or even recklessness does not satisfy the &ldquo;knowingly&rdquo; element required for a finding of perjury....</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>66. Such evidence might impair a witnesses' credibility, but not amount to perjury. Perjury in the civil context is defined identically to the definition contained in section 310 of the Criminal Code.
<QUOTE><P>131 (1) Subject to subsection (3), every one commits perjury who, with intent to mislead, makes before a person who is authorized by law to permit it to be made before him a false statement under oath or solemn affirmation, by affidavit, solemn declaration or deposition or orally, knowing that the statement is false.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>67. Here, it is said that the perjured evidence is not with respect to an occurrence or an event at issue in the proceedings, such as whether some transaction occurred, or whether some document was signed, or whether some agreement was made. The perjury, it is said, would impact on the trial judge's assessment of credibility.</P>
<P>68. The degree to which that must be so, in order for the Appellants to succeed, will be discussed later. It is useful to set out now, however, the principles, factors and considerations that go into an assessment of credibility.</P>
<P>69. It is one of the most discretionary decisions made by a trial judge, which explains the reluctance of this Court to interfere in such findings. This Court, it is frequently said, does not have the opportunity of observing the witness. Credibility involves much more, however, than merely observing the witness. In an oft cited passage, adopted by this Court, in <CASEREF><SOC>Bradshaw v. Stenner</SOC><CITE>2010, BCSC 1398</CITE></CASEREF>, Madam Justice Dillon said as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[186] Credibility involves an assessment of the trustworthiness of a witness' testimony based upon the veracity or sincerity of a witness and the accuracy of the evidence that the witness provides (<CASEREF><SOC>Raymond v. Bosanquet (Township)</SOC><YEAR>1919</YEAR><CITE>1919 CanLII 11</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>59 S.C.R. 452</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>50 D.L.R. 560</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>). The art of assessment involves examination of various factors such as the ability and opportunity to observe events, the firmness of his memory, the ability to resist the influence of interest to modify his recollection, whether the witness' evidence harmonizes with independent evidence that has been accepted, whether the witness changes his testimony during direct and cross-examination, whether the witness' testimony seems unreasonable, impossible, or unlikely, whether a witness has a motive to lie, and the demeanour of a witness generally (<CASEREF><SOC>Wallace v. Davis</SOC><CITE>[1926] 31 O.W.N. 202</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont.H.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Faryna v. Chorny</SOC><CITE>1951 CanLII 252</CITE><COURTJUR>BC CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1952] 2 D.L.R. 354</CITE><COURTJUR>B.C.C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> [<EM>Farnya</EM>]; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. S.(R.D.)</SOC><CITE>1997 CanLII 324</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1997] 3 S.C.R. 484</CITE><PARANUM>128</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>). Ultimately, the validity of the evidence depends on whether the evidence is consistent with the probabilities affecting the case as a whole and shown to be in existence at the time (<EM>Farnya</EM> at para. 356)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bradshaw v. Stenner</SOC><CITE>2010, BCSC 1398</CITE><PARANUM>186</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>70. Moreover, the court is entitled to accept some or all of a witnesses' testimony and a finding that certain aspects of a witnesses' testimony are not credible does not taint the entirety of his or her evidence. A judge is entitled to accept some, all, or none of a witnesses' testimony, even if the judge makes adverse findings of credibility on some particular aspect of that evidence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Graham v. Galaxie Signs Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 266</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>Revane v. Homersham</SOC><CITE>2006, BCCA 8</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>71. That inquiry is even more difficult at the level of this Court, when the Court must determine whether the fresh evidence could reasonably have been expected to have affected the credibility assessment of the actual trier of fact.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Ouellet</SOC><CITE>2010 BCCA 588</CITE><PARANUM>17 and 18</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>Consbec Inc. v. Walker</SOC><CITE>2006 BCCA 114</CITE><PARANUM>32 to 15</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>Burcevski v. Ambrozic</SOC><CITE>2010 ABQB 570</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>72. In cases where fresh evidence is sought to be introduced, to demonstrate fraud or perjury, the law tries to balance two competing principles&mdash;finality and the integrity of the process. There is, as the court says in <EM>Granitile</EM>, a &ldquo;tension in the core values of our legal system. There is a need to balance the desire for finality against the requirement that the court protect the integrity of its processes.&rdquo;</P>
<P>73. As the court says, the key is to find the right balance.
<P1><EM>Granitile</EM>, para. 2</P1>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Hummel</SOC><CITE>2003 YKCA 4</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>74. There are slight differences that have emerged in the implementation of the test, but all the authorities agree that as a starting point, the alleged perjury must be proved on a balance of probabilities, with clear and cogent evidence. The more serious the alleged fraud, the clearer and more cogent the evidence must be. (<EM>Granitile</EM>, paras. 283&ndash;289).</P>
<P>75. All of this has led to a restatement of the Palmer test in cases of fraud or perjury, although the fundamental principles of Palmer form the substratum of those requirements. In <CASEREF><SOC>International Corona Resources Ltd. v. LAC Minerals Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1988 CanLII 4534</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Mr. Justice Osbourne laid down a number of propositions. Those which are relevant to the case at bar are as follows:
<QUOTE><P>(1)The fraud alleged must be proved on a reasonable balance of probability. The more serious the fraud alleged, the more cogent the evidence going to establish it will have to be to meet the civil onus of proof. The reasonable balance of probability is not an inflexible standard of proof.</P>
<P>(2) The proved fraud must be material, that is, it must go to the foundation of the case.</P>
<P>(3) The evidence of fraud must not have been known at the time of trial to the party seeking to rely upon it on a motion to set aside a trial judgment.</P>
<P>(4) The unsuccessful trial party is exposed to a test of due or reasonable diligence. This is clear from cases such as, <CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald v. Pier</SOC></CASEREF>, supra; <CASEREF><SOC>Johnston v. Barkley</SOC></CASEREF>, supra, and <CASEREF><SOC>Industrial Development Bank v. Bertolo</SOC></CASEREF>, supra. In my view, the onus is on the moving party to establish due diligence....</P>
<P>(5) If the fraud alleged is that of a non-party, and if the successful party at trial is not connected with the fraud alleged, the tests to which I have referred must be more stringent than for the fraud of a party....</P>
<P>(6) The test imposed upon the unsuccessful trial party to obtain relevant evidence&mdash;that is, evidence going to establish fraud&mdash;with due diligence, is objective. The questions to be asked are: what did the moving party know, and what ought the moving party to have known?....</P>
<P>&ldquo;(9) At the end of the day, the central question to be answered is as stated in <CASEREF><SOC>Wentworth v. Rogers (No. 5)</SOC></CASEREF>, supra, at p. 538:</P>
<P>... it must be shown, by the party asserting that a judgment was procured by fraud, that there has been a new discovery of something material, in the sense that fresh facts have been found which, by themselves or in combination with previously known facts, would provide a reason for setting aside the judgment..</P></QUOTE>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>Coughlin v. Kuntz</SOC><CITE>1997 CanLII 2995</CITE><COURTJUR>BC SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rodenkirchen v. Peters</SOC><CITE>2006 BCSC 1021</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>76. Such differences as have arisen in the authorities as to the test to be applied fall into two areas&mdash;the requirement of due diligence, and the determination of the degree of impact the fresh evidence must have on the result. <EM>Corona</EM> clearly postulates a requirement that the evidence could not have been discovered by the exercise of due diligence, a requirement endorsed by Mr. Justice Cowan in the decision in Coughlin (paras. 32 to 36).</P>
<P>77. This court has held that applications such as these entail two distinct steps. Although in practical terms, they seem to merge, the proper process involves, first, determining whether the decision should be reconsidered at all, and secondly, whether it should be set aside.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Temple Consulting Group Ltd. v. Abakhan</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 119</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>78. The purpose of the due diligence requirement, which is considered as part of the first step, is to give weight to the value of finality in the balancing of the competing core values.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Nyoni</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 106</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>79. <EM>Corona</EM> postulates that the Appellants are &ldquo;exposed to a test of reasonable diligence&rdquo;. Tactical decisions, failure to call a witness, deliberate choices made, will not meet the standard. As was pointed out in <EM>Caughlin</EM>, however, the requirement of due diligence may have to be tempered, or at least considered in light of the fact that it is fraud of which the complaint is being made.</P>
<P>80. A truly clever fraudster, who does not even raise suspicion, It is said, surely cannot be allowed to retain the fruits of a judgment fraudulently obtained. However, even if fraud is alleged, the requirement of the demonstration of due diligence is essential to &ldquo;ensure finality and order, values essential to the integrity of the criminal process.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Nyoni</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 106</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>81. <EM>Granitile</EM> addresses the issue at some length, and while some of its reasoning, perhaps, seems a little fine (para. 307) after a careful analysis, it rests its decision on the proposition that, in cases involving fraud, the test of due diligence is an objective one&mdash;&ldquo;what did the moving party know, and what ought the moving party to have known.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Granitile</EM>, para. 108</P1></P>
<P>82. The Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Albert v. Politano</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 194</CITE></CASEREF>, expresses the test in similar terms.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Albert v. Politano</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 194</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>83. The presence of fraud raises similar difficulties in assessing the degree of impact on the final result. The allegations must meet in order to engage the court's juris diction. The starting point of the analysis is, once again, <EM>Corona</EM>, which holds that the inquiry must be with regard to a material matter, and goes on to say:
<QUOTE><P>It seems to me the word &ldquo;material&rdquo; means that which goes to the foundation of the decision or which goes to the crux of a central issue before the court. &ldquo;Material&rdquo; obviously means something different from and, in this context, more than &ldquo;relevant&rdquo;; it means more than evidence which would be an appropriate topic for cross-examination on credibility, but collateral in the sense of being divorced from any of the main issues in the case in a trial</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>84. <EM>Granitile</EM> holds that while the fraud must be material, it is not necessary that there be a finding that it is &ldquo;determinative of the decision being attacked&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Granitile</EM>, para. 315</P1></P>
<P>85. The Ontario Court of Appeal, in <CASEREF><SOC>100 Main Street East Ltd. v. Sakas</SOC><CITE>1975 CanLII 381</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, speaks, once again, of the need of balancing the needs of certainty and finality with the need to protect the integrity of the system, and puts the proposition this way:
<QUOTE><P>These authorities make it clear that the new evidence of fraud must relate to the &ldquo;foundation&rdquo; of the decision or be &ldquo;material&rdquo; to the claim or defence, but need not necessarily amount to a &ldquo;determining factor in the result&rdquo;. Duff, J., in a dissenting opinion in <CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald v. Pier</SOC><CITE>1922 CanLII 29</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1923] S.C.R. 107</CITE><PAGENUM>at pp. 120-1</PAGENUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[1923] 1 D.L.R. 670</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> at pp. 680-1, [1923] 1 W.W.R. 376, in discussing this principle, stated:</P>
<P>... there is jurisdiction in the court to entertain an action to set aside a judgment on the ground that it has been obtained through perjury. The principle I conceive to be this; such jurisdiction exists but in the exercise of it the court will not permit its process to be made use of and will exert the utmost care and caution to prevent its process being used for the purpose of obtaining a retrial of an issue already determined, of an issue which transivit in rem judicatam under the guise of impugning a judgment as procured by fraud. Therefore the perjury must be in a material matter and therefore it must be established by evidence not known to the parties at the time of the former trial.</P>
<P>The process appears to be one of balancing the need for the Courts to protect the integrity of their process against fraudulent practices before the Court, on the one hand, against the practical requirement of certainty and finality in litigation on the other. The latter principle is expressed by Lord Justice James in <CASEREF><SOC>Flower v. Lloyd</SOC><YEAR>1878</YEAR><CITE>10 Ch. D. 327</CITE><PAGENUM>at pp. 333-4</PAGENUM></CASEREF>: ...</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>86. Perhaps the most practical statement is that contained in the Alberta Court of Appeal judgment of <CASEREF><SOC>Hill v. Hill</SOC></CASEREF>. The court there was considering the case of a chambers judge who had indicated that the fresh evidence in question was required to be &ldquo;practically conclusive&rdquo; before the judgment could be set aside, and concluded that the various postulations of the test were merely different ways of saying the same thing.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hill v. Hill</SOC><CITE>2016 ABCA 49</CITE><PARANUM>55 and 56</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>87. Applying that test to an issue of credibility, however, involves weighing the perjured evidence within the multi-faceted elements that go into a trial judge's assessment of a witnesses' credibility. The question is, considering the totality of the evidence at the trial, whether the evidence in question could inpune the offending witnesses' testimony to the extent of reasonably affecting the outcome of the trial.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Nyoni</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 106</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>88. The same proposition was advanced in <CASEREF><SOC>Kiskadee Ventures Limited v. 2164017 Ontario Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 955</CITE></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>[21] The admissibility of the fresh evidence turns on whether that evidence, considered with the rest of the evidence adduced at trial, could be expected to have affected the result or, more specifically, could be expected to have affected the trial judge's assessment of Mr. Narine's credibility: see <CASEREF><SOC>Ontario Federation of Anglers and Hunters v. Ontario (Ministry of Natural Resources)</SOC><CITE>2002 CanLII 41606</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[2002] O.J. No. 1445</CITE><PARANUM>63</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>. If the answer is yes, the fresh evidence is admissible and a new trial must be ordered. If the answer is no, the evidence is not admissible on appeal.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kiskadee Ventures Limited v. 2164017 Ontario Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 955</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">IV. <UNDER>Application of the Law to the Facts</UNDER></TI>
<P>89. The above discussion establishes that the Appellants must:
<P1>(a) Establish the complained of evidence was perjured, with clear and compelling evidence;</P1>
<P1>(b) Establish that they exercised due diligence with respect to the evidence now relied on to establish the perjury, as that concept is applied in cases of fraud; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Demonstrate that the evidence would have had a material and substantive impact on the judge's assessment, both of the credibility of Mr. Darch, and on the result of the trial.</P1></P>
<P>90. The Appellants cannot do any of those three things.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">V. <UNDER>Was There Perjury?</UNDER></TI>
<P>91. The first element that must be established, with cogent and compelling evidence, is that there was perjury in the first place. Perjury is false evidence, knowingly given, with the intent to mislead. In a broad brush way, the allegation is that the Learned Trial Judge found Mr. Darch to be an unbiased witness, not interested by friendship or financial interests, and that he was, therefore, a credible witness.</P>
<P>92. It must be remembered, first of all, that the allegations of perjury do not go to the substance of Mr. Darch's evidence on the merits, but are restricted to the assessment of his credibility.</P>
<P>93. In the second place, with the exception of the allegation of providing financial assistance, the alleged perjury is not as to some specific, concrete and provable fact: did you say this to the police?; did you ever use a different name?; were you ever convicted of this offence?; etc. The allegation of perjury is as to a more nebulous concept, both requiring clarification and agreement on a definition. Did you provide &ldquo;assistance&rdquo;?; are you &ldquo;biased&rdquo;?</P>
<P>94. The allegation that financial assistance was provided is simply untrue. An explanation has been provided for the fact that Clark Wilson's ledgers record payments received on behalf of Mr. Long from Mr. Darch's company or, in some cases, from Mr. Darch.</P>
<P>95. The facts, however, are that Mr. Long resided in Bangkok, he had no readily accessible bank account, he was credited with funds he had earned under his employment contract, and rather than being paid directly to him, those funds were distributed on his behalf. They were distributed to relatives, and to other parties, including Clark Wilson.</P>
<P>96. The explanation of Mr. Darch and Mr. Long is corroborated by documents. An email of June 7, 2013, refers to Mr. Darch making an advance if only a particular payment had been received. Other documents show that the funds were sent to various locations, not just sent to Clark Wilson to provide dollars to run the lawsuit. The evidence of Mr. Long and Mr. Darch is fully corroborated by those documents. The denial of providing financial assistance was not false, let alone knowingly false, or made with an intention to mislead.
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Mr. Darch, Exhibit C, pg. 7</P1></P>
<P>97. Whether Mr. Darch provided assistance in other ways, is far more nebulous a question. Without exploring, in cross-examination the particulars of what was meant by &ldquo;providing assistance&rdquo; it is impossible for the Appellants to present cogent and compelling evidence that the denial was perjury. To the extent that there was an example given in cross, it focused on financial assistance&mdash;arranging for a job so that Mr. Long would funds to carry on the lawsuit. In terms of Mr. Darch's understanding of the providing of assistance, in his affidavit, Mr. Darch says as follows:
<QUOTE><P>33. I also stand by my assertion that I provided no assistance to Mr. Long in this litigation. I considered assistance, when I was asked that question, to be something concrete, such as the arranging for counsel, a contribution to legal fees, or, as was put to me in cross-examination, creating a job for Mr. Long so that he would have the wherewithal to fund this litigation.</P>
<P>34. I did not consider it providing assistance to Mr. Long to be a witness and, as a witness, to advise both he and his lawyers as to what my evidence was and as to what documents I was aware of, as a witness, which would be relevant to the litigation. In my view, that is the obligation of every witness, and I did not, and do not view that as providing assistance to Mr. Long in the litigation, but rather as doing my duty. I alluded to that view in my evidence at trial.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Mr. Darch, paras. 33 and 34</P1></P>
<P>98. At trial, on the question of the meaning of the providing of assistance, Mr. Darch said the following:
<QUOTE><P>A: I have not been assisting Mr. Long in the litigation. I gave him this information at the time, that if he was being denied something which he claimed was justly his, then it would be inappropriate of me not to tell him where he might find the proof that he needs.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Memorandum, pg. 6</P1></P>
<P>99. Mr. Darch maintained, both then and now, that he did not provide assistance as he understood it. Instead, he performed his duty, as someone who was asked to be a witness should do. Moreover, he frankly testified, at trial, and the Appellants were well aware, that he gave &ldquo;assistance&rdquo; in the very sense about which it is now argued he lied. Mr. Darch testified:
<P1>(a) He had discussed the case with Mr. Long;</P1>
<P1>(b) He had met with Mr. Long's lawyers;</P1>
<P1>(c) He had provided documents to those lawyers; and</P1>
<P1>(d) He had met with the Andersons and discussed the merits of the case with them.</P1></P>
<P>100. His general statement, therefore, that he had not provided assistance, must be assessed in light of the other evidence he provided at trial, and perjury cannot be established by producing hitherto privileged emails which simply show that he engaged in the very activities he testified he engaged in at trial, but which give more particulars of that evidence. That is a total non sequitur, particularly as his answers were not probed at all on cross-examination.</P>
<P>101. As in <CASEREF><SOC>Liedtke-Thompson v. Gignac</SOC><CITE>2014 YKCA 10</CITE></CASEREF>, the first question is was there perjury at all? One cannot point to emails showing that Mr. Darch met with lawyers, provided information to lawyers, provided documents to lawyers, met with witnesses, and discussed the matter with Mr. Long as being evidence of perjury when Mr. Darch had already said he did all of those things in his evidence.</P>
<P>102. In so far as Mr. Long is concerned, the complaint is that Mr. Long testified at trial that he did not discuss the matter with Mr. Darch. However, the trial judge was aware, from the cross-examination, of the contradiction between Mr. Long's evidence and Mr. Darch's evidence on that score and to the extent that that affected Mr. Long's credibility, it must have been included in the trial judge's assessment of the case.</P>
<P>103. Moreover, there is no evidence at all to suggest anything other than that Long's memory was faded. Indeed, in one of his responses, he seemed to confirm that he had received some advice from Mr. Darch! That apparent contradiction in his own evidence, together with the contradiction with Mr. Darch's evidence, was not explored on cross-examination, but it was a conflict which was part of the evidence at trial weighed by the trial judge and cannot come as a surprise to anyone.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">VI. <UNDER>Due Diligence</UNDER></TI>
<P>104. All of the above facts impact not only the question of whether there was perjury, but impact the issue of due diligence. One need not go so far as the postulation of the test in <EM>Corona</EM> to say that there was none. Assuming the test is as postulated in <EM>Granitile</EM>, an objective test that the Appellants either knew or ought to have known of the evidence, the Appellants still fail.</P>
<P>105. The Appellants knew, and the evidence at trial included, so the Learned Trial Judge also knew:
<P1>(a) There had been vituperative litigation between Mr. Wright and Mr. Darch;</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Darch and Mr. Long were business partners and friends for a period of time;</P1>
<P1>(c) Mr. Darch had met with Mr. Long's lawyers;</P1>
<P1>(d) Mr. Darch had provided documents to Mr. Long's lawyers;</P1>
<P1>(e) Mr. Darch had met with the Andersons; and</P1>
<P1>(f) Mr. Darch had had discussions with Mr. Long about the litigation.</P1></P>
<P>106. The Appellants must also be taken to have known what a cooperating witness normally does. Such a witness does meet with lawyers, he does produce documents to those lawyers, he does discuss the case with the party and counsel on whose behalf he is being called. It is inevitable that he identifies, in an adversarial process, to some extent, with the party calling him as a witness. That is neither sinister nor evidence of bias.</P>
<P>107. If it is the position of the Respondent that if the emails do in fact disclose conduct which the Court considers over and above what would normally be expected from a cooperating witness, then the Appellants certainly knew enough of the facts to press the points vigorously on cross-examination, to see what could be elicited. The cross-examination on the issue of providing assistance was somewhat tepid, but it is equally telling that there was no effort at all made to interview Mr. Darch prior to trial.</P>
<P>108. There is no property in a witness. Indeed, the <EM>Supreme Court Rules</EM> and the necessity of filing Trial Briefs are to identify witnesses to the other side precisely so that the evidence they might give can be canvassed with one's own client, and so one can contact the witness to ascertain what it is they might say.</P>
<P>109. The Appellants were told, three times, that Mr. Darch was going to be called as a witness. That requirement is imposed in the <EM>Rules</EM> to get rid of ambush, precisely so that the witness <UNDER>can</UNDER> be contacted and his evidence discussed. There was ample opportunity, both prior to trial, and on cross-examination, to launch an inquiry as to whether there was any bias on the part of Mr. Darch, and enough facts were known, or ought to have been known, to place an onus upon the Appellants to pursue the issue more thoroughly than they did.</P>
<P>110. It is interesting to determine what inference can be drawn from Mr. Wright's failure to contact Mr. Darch. It has been held that the failure of a lawyer to interview a potential witness is negligence.</P>
<P>111. The inference that competent and capable trial counsel was negligent ought not to be drawn. The proper inference to draw is that Mr. Wright made a deliberate decision not to have his lawyer contact Mr. Darch because he knew precisely what it was Mr. Darch would tell that lawyer, and he did not view contacting him as a fruitful exercise for his lawyer to engage in. As to bias arising from the relationships between Mr. Wright and Mr. Darch, the facts of that litigation were obviously known to Mr. Wright, but once again, they were not put to Mr. Darch on cross-examination.</P>
<P>112. The facts of the Darch/ Long relationship were also known and disclosed at trial as being a business and friendly relationship. However, as deposed to in the current affidavits, Mr. Darch and Mr. Long were no longer associates or friends by the time of tri al, and had not seen each other since 2014.</P>
<P>113. The Appellants cannot demonstrate, on the basis of any definition, that they have discharged the burden of due diligence.</P>
<P>114. The final question is the impact the evidence had on the assessment of credibility and the ultimate determination at trial.</P>
<P>115. This case did not turn upon Mr. Darch being unbiased and not having provided assistance to Mr. Long. The assessment of Mr. Darch's credibility did not turn solely upon the trial judge's determination of a lack of bias although, obviously, that was a factor in his determination. There are, at the end of the day, only two questions.</P>
<P>116. Had the trial judge known that Mr. Darch sent the emails in June, December and February, and undertaken the activities those emails disclose, would the trial judge's assessment of Mr. Darch's credibility be any different? Given that those activities being undertaken by Mr. Darch would not surprise the trial judge, as they are what any witness does, were testified to by Darch, and given that the contents of those emails, (in so far as they go to the merits), in fact bolster Mr. Darch's credibility, it is difficult to see how that knowledge would have caused the trial judge to reach an adverse conclusion as to credibility. That is particularly so given that Darch's evidence was consistent with the evidence of Mark Andrews, Q.C., Mr. Long, certain of the documents, what Mr. Wright had said to other people, and the probability that his evidence was correct, weighed against the other evidence.</P>
<P>117. <EM>A fortiori</EM>, the trial decision, which was not based solely upon the credibility of Mr. Darch, who was only a corroborating witness, but was based rather on an assessment, as required, of the totality of the evidence, it is impossible to conclude that had the emails now attached to the affidavit of Ms. Hambrook, been placed in evidence at the trial, the outcome of the trial would have differed in the slightest.</P>
<P>118. The application should be dismissed. Special costs should be awarded for these unfounded and scandalous assertions.</P>
<P>Dated this 19<SUP>th</SUP> day of December, 2017.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellip35; Counsel for the Respondent</P>
<P>H.C. Ritchie Clark, Q.C.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
